Overall, the figures in the 2012 survey suggest that the percentage of Muslims in the countries surveyed who approve the death penalty for Muslims who leave Islam to become an atheist or convert to another religion varies widely, from 0.4% (in Kazakhstan) to 78.2% (in Afghanistan).<ref name=pew2013apo>{{cite web |url=http://www.pewforum.org/2013/04/30/the-worlds-muslims-religion-politics-society-beliefs-about-sharia/ |title=Beliefs about Sharia |publisher=Pew Research Center |date=2013-04-30 |accessdate=2014-08-30 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140830232031/http://www.pewforum.org/2013/04/30/the-worlds-muslims-religion-politics-society-beliefs-about-sharia/ |archivedate=30 August 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The Governments of the [[Gulf Cooperation Council]] (Saudi Arabia, UAE, Oman, Qatar, Bahrain and Kuwait) did not permit Pew Research to survey nationwide public opinion on apostasy in 2010 or 2012. The survey also did not include [[China]], [[India]], [[Syria]], or [[West Africa]]n countries such as [[Nigeria]].

=== Afghanistan ===
{{Main|Freedom of religion in Afghanistan|Human rights in Afghanistan}}
{{See also|Talibanization|Islam in Afghanistan|Religion in Afghanistan}}
Article 130 of the [[Constitution of Afghanistan|Afghan Constitution]] requires its courts to apply provisions of Hanafi Sunni fiqh for crimes of apostasy in Islam. Article 1 of the [[Law of Afghanistan|Afghan Penal Code]] requires [[hudud]] crimes be punished per Hanafi religious jurisprudence. Prevailing Hanafi jurisprudence, per consensus of its school of Islamic scholars, prescribes death penalty for the crime of apostasy. The apostate can avoid prosecution and/or punishment if he or she confesses of having made a mistake of apostasy and rejoins Islam.<ref>[https://www.loc.gov/law/help/apostasy/index.php#afghanistan Afghanistan - Laws Criminalizing Apostasy] {{webarchive|url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20171231144725/https://www.loc.gov/law/help/apostasy/index.php |date=31 December 2017 }} Library of Congress (May 2014)</ref>
In addition to death, the family of the accused can be deprived of all property and possessions, and the individual's marriage is considered dissolved in accordance with Hanafi Sunni jurisprudence.<ref>{{cite web|work=U.S. Department of State|date=20 May 2013|title=Bureau of Democracy, Human Rights and Labor, International Religious Freedom Report for 2012: Afghanistan 3–4|url=https://www.state.gov/documents/organization/208634.pdf|format=PDF|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170504010751/https://www.state.gov/documents/organization/208634.pdf|archivedate=4 May 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

In March 2006, an Afghan citizen [[Abdul Rahman (convert)|Abdul Rahman]] was charged with apostasy and could have faced the death penalty for converting to [[Christianity in Afghanistan|Christianity]]. His case attracted much international attention with [[Western world|Western countries]] condemning Afghanistan for persecuting a convert. Charges against Abdul Rahman were dismissed on technical grounds by the Afghan court after intervention by the president [[Hamid Karzai]]. He was released and left the country to find refuge in [[Italy]].<ref name=marshall20080410/>

Two other Afghan converts to Christianity, Sayed Mussa and Shoaib Assadullah, were arrested back in March 2006. In February 2006, the homes of yet other converts were raided by [[Afghan National Police|police]].<ref name=marshall20080410/> After serving five years in jail, Sayed Mussa was released in 2011,<ref name="mussa-release">{{Cite news|last1=Vogt|first1=Heidi|last2=Schrek|first2=Adam|title=Jailed Christian convert is freed in Afghanistan|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2011/02/25/AR2011022501007.html|date=25 February 2011|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170102114854/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2011/02/25/AR2011022501007.html|archivedate=2 January 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and Shoaib Assadullah was released in March 2011.<ref name="shoaib-release">{{cite web|title=Afghan Christian released from prison and safely out of the country|url=http://www.christiantoday.com/article/afghan.christian.released.from.prison.and.safely.out.of.the.country/27869.htm|date=23 April 2011|accessdate=9 April 2016|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20171019020017/https://www.christiantoday.com/article/afghan.christian.released.from.prison.and.safely.out.of.the.country/27869.htm|archivedate=19 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

In 2012, secular university teacher Javeed from [[Ghazni Province]] wrote an article criticising the [[Taliban]] in English. The Taliban tried to seize him, but he and his wife Marina, a well-known Afgan television host, decided to flee to the [[Netherlands]]. When in 2014 it was translated to [[Pashto]] by powerful warlord [[Gulbuddin Hekmatyar]]'s son-in-law, this led to an uproar on social media with many accusations of apostasy and death threats directed at Javeed, and a large public demonstration in [[Kabul]] calling for his execution.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.human.nl/2doc/2016/ongelovig.html |title=Non-believers: Freethinkers on the Run |author=Dorothée Forma |work=Human |date=2 September 2015 |accessdate=3 October 2017 |language=nl |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171019020022/https://www.human.nl/2doc/2016/ongelovig.html |archivedate=19 October 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

In late 2015, 21-year-old student and ex-Muslim atheist Morid Aziz had a religious argument with his girlfriend Shogofa, once a liberal Muslim, but radicalised whilst studying Sharia. She secretly recorded the conversation, during which he criticised Islam, and begged her to 'forsake the darkness and embrace science', but she called him a ''kafir'' and said he would burn in hell. The next day, she played the recording at the Friday prayer in a full mosque. Aziz was inundated with questions from relatives about how he had dared to say what he said, and he quickly went into hiding just before angry men armed with [[Kalashnikov rifle|Kalashnikovs]] showed up at his house. 23 days later, he fled across several countries and ended up in the [[Netherlands]], where he obtained [[permanent residency]] on 30 May 2017.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.volkskrant.nl/buitenland/morid-twijfelde-over-zijn-geloof-zijn-vriendin-verlinkte-hem-in-een-volle-moskee-in-afghanistan~a4543276/ |title=Morid twijfelde over zijn geloof, zijn vriendin verlinkte hem in een volle moskee in Afghanistan |author=Janny Groen |work=de Volkskrant |date=5 December 2017 |accessdate=8 December 2017 |language=nl |quote=We hadden een heftig gesprek. Ze noemde mij een kafir, zei dat ik zwaar zou worden gestraft in het hiernamaals, dat ik zou branden in de hel. Ik smeekte haar de duisternis te verlaten, naar het licht te komen, de wetenschap te omarmen. |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171208070717/https://www.volkskrant.nl/buitenland/morid-twijfelde-over-zijn-geloof-zijn-vriendin-verlinkte-hem-in-een-volle-moskee-in-afghanistan~a4543276/ |archivedate=8 December 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

=== Algeria ===
{{Main|Freedom of religion in Algeria}}
[[File:Djemila BenHabib - Why Islamists are Gaining Ground.webm|thumb|[[Djemila Benhabib]]: "Freedom of conscience has never been recognised", and Islam is not separated from the state.]]

Freedom of religion in [[Algeria]] is regulated by the Algerian Constitution, which declares Sunni Islam to be the state religion<ref name="FOTR17dz">{{Cite web |url=http://freethoughtreport.com/countries/africa-northern-africa/algeria/ |title=Algeria |work=Freedom of Thought Report 2017 |publisher=International Humanist and Ethical Union |date=4 December 2017 |accessdate=11 December 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171211105140/http://freethoughtreport.com/countries/africa-northern-africa/algeria/ |archivedate=11 December 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> (Article 2) but also declares that "freedom of creed and opinion is inviolable" (Article 36);{{citation needed|date=November 2017}} it prohibits discrimination, Article 29 states "All citizens are equal before the law. No discrimination shall prevail because of birth, race, sex, opinion or any other personal or social condition or circumstance".{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}

According to [[Pew Research Center]] in 2010, 97.9% of Algerians were Muslim, 1.8% were unaffiliated, with the remaining 0.3% comprising adherents of other religions.<ref name=pew>[http://www.globalreligiousfutures.org/countries/algeria/religious_demography#/?affiliations_religion_id=0&affiliations_year=2010 Pew Research Center's Religion & Public Life Project: Algeria] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131216182816/http://www.globalreligiousfutures.org/countries/algeria/religious_demography |date=16 December 2013 }}. [[Pew Research Center]]. 2010.</ref>

By law, children follow the religion of their fathers, even if they are born abroad and are citizens of their (non-Muslim-majority) country of birth.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}} The study of Islam is a requirement in the public and private [[school]]s for every Algerian child, irrespective of his/her religion.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.algerie-dz.com/article841.html |title=Ecoles privées en Algérie : Plaidoyer pour le bilinguisme |accessdate=2005-02-06 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050302223610/http://www.algerie-dz.com/article841.html |archivedate=2 March 2005 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Although the educational reform of 2006 eliminated "Islamic sciences" from the baccalaureate, Islamic studies are mandatory in public schools at primary level and followed by Sharia studies at secondary level. Concerns have been expressed that requests by non-Muslim religious students to opt out of these classes would result in discrimination.<ref name="FOTR17dz"/>

Muslim women cannot marry non-Muslim men ([[Algerian Family Code]] I.II.31),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lexalgeria.net/droitdelafamille.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-12-04 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040623101746/http://www.lexalgeria.net/droitdelafamille.htm |archivedate=2004-06-23 |df= }}</ref> and Muslim men may not marry women of non-monotheistic religious groups.<ref name="FOTR17dz"/> Prior to the 2005 amendments, family law stated that if it is established that either spouse is an "apostate" from Islam, the marriage will be declared null and void (Family Code I.III.32).<ref name="FOTR17dz"/> The term "apostate" was removed with the amendments, however those determined as such still cannot receive any inheritance (Family Code III.I.138).<ref name="FOTR17dz"/>

People without religious affiliation tend to be particularly numerous in [[Kabylie]] (a [[Kabyle language|Kabyle-speaking]] area) where they are generally tolerated and sometimes supported.<ref name="FOTR17dz"/> Notably, Berber civil rights, human rights and secular activist and musician [[Lounès Matoub]] (assassinated in 1998) is widely seen as a hero among [[Kabyle people|Kabyles]], despite (or because of) his lack of religion.<ref>{{Cite book |last1=Bullivant |first1=Stephen |last2=Ruse |first2=Michael |date=2013 |title=The Oxford Handbook of Atheism |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=93VoAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA722 |location=Oxford |publisher=Oxford University Press |page=722 |isbn=9780191667398 |accessdate=11 December 2017}}</ref> In most other areas of the country, the non-religious tend to be more discreet, and often pretend to be pious Muslims to avoid violence and lynching.<ref name="FOTR17dz"/>

The majority of cases of harassment and security threats against non-Muslims come from the now nearly destroyed [[Armed Islamic Group]], an organization fighting the government who are determined to rid the country of those who do not share their extremist interpretation of Islam.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}} However, a majority of the population subscribes to Islamic precepts of tolerance in religious beliefs.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}} Moderate Islamist religious and political leaders{{Who|date=November 2017}} have criticized publicly acts of violence committed in the name of Islam.

The "blasphemy" law is stringent and widely enforced. The non-religious are largely invisible in the public sphere, and although not specifically targeted through legislation, significant prejudice towards non-Muslim religions can be presumed to apply equally if not more so to non-believers.<ref name="FOTR17dz"/> The crime of "blasphemy" carries a maximum of five years in prison and the laws are interpreted widely. For example, several arrests have been made under the blasphemy laws in the last few years for failure to fast during Ramadan, even though this is not a requirement under Algerian law. Non-fasting persons ("non-jeûneurs") repeatedly face harassment by the police and civil society.<ref name="FOTR17dz"/> Eating in public during [[Ramadan]] (particularly for people who "look Muslim") is legal, but attracts public hostility in most areas, except for some areas of [[Kabylie]].{{citation needed|date=November 2017}} Most restaurants close during Ramadan.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}

In general, non-citizens who practice faiths other than Islam enjoy a high level of tolerance within society; however, citizens who renounce Islam generally are ostracized by their families and shunned by their neighbors.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}} Those who "renounce" Islam may be imprisoned, fined, or co-erced to re-convert.<ref name="FOTR17dz"/> The Government generally does not become involved in such disputes.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}} Converts also expose themselves to the risk of attack by radical extremists.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}

=== Bangladesh ===
[[File:Bonya Ahmed - We Stand on the Right Side of History.webm|thumb|[[Bonya Ahmed]] speaking about the attack on her and [[Avijit Roy]] (18:54), and putting it in a broader context.]]
{{Main|Freedom of religion in Bangladesh|Human rights in Bangladesh}}
{{See also|Islam in Bangladesh|Religion in Bangladesh|Attacks by Islamic extremists in Bangladesh}}
[[Islam in Bangladesh|Bangladesh]] does not have a law against apostasy, but incidences of persecution of apostates have been reported. ome Bangladeshi Imams{{Who|date=November 2017}} have encouraged the killing of converts from Islam.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}} The radical Islamist group [[Hefazat-e-Islam Bangladesh]], founded in 2010, created a hit list which included 83 outspoken atheist or secularist activists, including ex-Muslim bloggers and academics.<ref name="Jaeger">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nrc.nl/nieuws/2018/03/16/ik-dacht-waarom-bewijst-god-dan-niet-dat-ie-bestaat-a1595999 |title='Ik dacht: waarom bewijst God dan niet dat-ie bestaat?' |author=Toef Jaeger |work=NRC Handelsblad |date=16 March 2018 |accessdate=19 March 2018 |language=nl |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180320224424/https://www.nrc.nl/nieuws/2018/03/16/ik-dacht-waarom-bewijst-god-dan-niet-dat-ie-bestaat-a1595999 |archivedate=20 March 2018 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Dozens of atheist and secularist Bangladeshis on this list have been targeted for practicing free speech and "disrespecting" Islam, such as [[Humayun Azad]], who was the target of a failed machete assassination attempt, and [[Avijit Roy]], who was killed with meat cleavers; his wife [[Bonya Ahmed]] survived the attack.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-31819649 |title=Widow of blogger Avijit Roy defiant after Bangladesh attack |work=BBC News |date=10 March 2015 |accessdate=19 March 2018 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314034356/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-31819649 |archivedate=14 March 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Since 2013, 8 of the 83 people on the hit list have been killed; 31 others have fled the country.<ref name="Jaeger"/>

=== Belgium ===
[[File:Comité van ex-moslims in België.svg|thumb|Movement of Ex-Muslims of [[Belgium]].]]
{{Main|Freedom of religion in Belgium|Irreligion in Belgium|Organized secularism}}
In the Western European country of [[Belgium]], [[Islam in Belgium|Muslims made up]] about 5 to 7% of the total population as of 2015.<ref name="npdata.be">{{cite web |url=http://www.npdata.be |publisher=Npdata.be |title=Moslims in België per gewest, provincie en gemeente |date=18 September 2015 |accessdate=3 March 2016 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304090217/http://www.npdata.be/ |archivedate=4 March 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Although legally anyone is free to change their religion, there is a social taboo on apostatising from Islam.<ref name="horen">{{Cite news |url=https://www.demorgen.be/opinie/afvallige-moslims-laat-van-u-horen-jullie-zijn-met-meer-dan-jullie-denken-b79aa042/ |title=Afvallige moslims, laat van u horen. Jullie zijn met meer dan jullie denken |author=[[Maarten Boudry]] |work=De Morgen |date=9 March 2017 |accessdate=6 October 2017 |language=nl |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171007120041/https://www.demorgen.be/opinie/afvallige-moslims-laat-van-u-horen-jullie-zijn-met-meer-dan-jullie-denken-b79aa042/ |archivedate=7 October 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Moroccan-Belgian stand-up comedian Sam Touzani is a rare example an outspoken ex-Muslim;<ref name="horen"/> he was condemned by several fatwas and has received hundreds of death threats online, but persists in his criticism of Islam and Islamism.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.demorgen.be/binnenland/-de-21ste-eeuw-moet-weer-leren-lachen-b72a6aa8/ |title="De 21ste eeuw moet weer leren lachen" |author=Lode Delputte |work=De Morgen |date=9 March 2017 |accessdate=6 October 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171007115845/https://www.demorgen.be/binnenland/-de-21ste-eeuw-moet-weer-leren-lachen-b72a6aa8/ |archivedate=7 October 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

A Movement of Ex-Muslims of Belgium exists to support apostates from Islam, and to 'fight Islamic indoctrination'. As of 2014, it had a dozen members, who had to operate carefully and often anonymously.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://tempsreel.nouvelobs.com/societe/20141120.AFP1286/en-europe-les-apostats-de-l-islam-commencent-a-se-compter.html |title=En Europe, les apostats de l'islam commencent à se compter |author= |work=[[Le Nouvel Observateur]] |date=20 November 2014 |accessdate=6 October 2017 |language=fr |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171019020020/http://tempsreel.nouvelobs.com/societe/20141120.AFP1286/en-europe-les-apostats-de-l-islam-commencent-a-se-compter.html |archivedate=19 October 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Additionally, Belgian academics such as [[Maarten Boudry]] and Johan Leman have led efforts to try to normalize leaving Islam in Belgium.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.demorgen.be/binnenland/maarten-boudry-zocht-en-vond-ex-moslims-b9b88ebe/|title=Maarten Boudry zocht en vond ex-moslims|author=Bruno Struys|date=9 March 2017|work=De Morgen|accessdate=6 October 2017|language=nl|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171007115955/https://www.demorgen.be/binnenland/maarten-boudry-zocht-en-vond-ex-moslims-b9b88ebe/|archivedate=7 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 16 November 2017, 25-year-old Hamza, shunned by his family (except for his supportive sister), came out as an ex-Muslim on television. He was seconded by philosopher and ex-Catholic Patrick Loobuyck, who argued that secularisation in the West gives Western Muslims such as the opportunity to embrace religious liberalism and even atheism.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/nl/2017/11/16/-ik-geloof-niet-meer-in-allah-/ |title=Hamza (25) is geen moslim meer: "Bewust ervoor gekozen om niet gelovig te zijn" |author=Joris Truyts |work=VRT Nieuws |date=16 November 2017 |accessdate=18 November 2017 |language=nl |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201030529/https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/nl/2017/11/16/-ik-geloof-niet-meer-in-allah-/ |archivedate=1 December 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

=== Bosnia and Herzegovina ===
{{Main|Religion in Bosnia and Herzegovina}}
During the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman Turkish Muslim rule]] of [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] (1463–1878), a large minority of the Southern Slavic-speaking inhabitants converted to Islam for various reasons, whilst others remained Roman Catholics (later known as Croats) or Orthodox Christians (later known as Serbs). These converts and their descendants were simply known as "Bosnian Muslims" or just "Muslims", until the term [[Bosniaks]] was adopted in 1993. Not all Bosniaks (still) practice Islam nowadays; some may just be "Muslim" by name or cultural background, but not by conviction, profession or practice.<ref>{{Cite book |last1=Bideleux |first1=Robert |last2=Jeffries |first2=Ian |date=2007 |title=The Balkans: A Post-Communist History |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=G6iBAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA330 |location=New York |publisher=Routledge |pages=330–331 |isbn=9781134583287 |accessdate=2 January 2018 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171019155238/https://books.google.com/books?id=G6iBAgAAQBAJ |archivedate=19 October 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In a 1998 public opinion poll, just 78.3% of Bosniaks in the [[Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina]] declared themselves to be religious.<ref>{{cite book|title=Religious separation and political intolerance in Bosnia-Herzegovina|last1=Velikonja|first1=Mitja|authorlink=|year=2003|publisher=Texas A&M University Press|location=|isbn=978-1-58544-226-3|page=261|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Rf8P-7ExoKYC&pg=PA261|accessdate=6 January 2011|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130530042237/http://books.google.com/books?id=Rf8P-7ExoKYC&pg=PA261|archivedate=30 May 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

The Ottomans punished apostasy from Islam with the death penalty until the [[Edict of Toleration 1844]]; subsequently, apostates could be imprisoned or deported instead.<ref name="Duijzings 2000 86–99">{{cite book|last=Duijzings|first=Ger|title=Religion and the Politics of Identity in Kosovo|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aJRYkzl5YC4C|year=2000|publisher=C. Hurst & Co. Publishers|isbn=978-1-85065-431-5|pages=86–99|ref=harv|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160516185635/https://books.google.com/books?id=aJRYkzl5YC4C|archivedate=16 May 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> When [[Austria-Hungary]] occupied Bosnia and Herzegovina in 1878, this practice was abolished. The Austrian government held that any mature citizen was free to convert to another religion without having to fear any legal penalty, and issued a directive to its officials to keep their involvement in religious matters to a minimum. This clashed with the rigorous hostility to conversion exhibited by traditional Bosnian Muslims, who perceived it as a threat to the survival of Islam. During the four decades of Habsburg rule, several apostasy controversies occurred, most often involving young women with a low socio-economic status who sought to convert to Christianity.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Pinson |first=Mark |date=1996 |title=The Muslims of Bosnia-Herzegovina: Their Historic Development from the Middle Ages to the Dissolution of Yugoslavia |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Yl3TAkJmztYC&pg=PA99 |location=Cambridge, Massachusetts |publisher=Harvard CMES |pages=99–101 |isbn=9780932885128 |accessdate=4 January 2018 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160518060654/https://books.google.com/books?id=Yl3TAkJmztYC |archivedate=18 May 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

In August 1890, during the [[Austro-Hungarian rule in Bosnia and Herzegovina]], a sixteen-year-old Bosnian girl called Uzeifa Delahmatović claimed to have voluntarily converted from Islam to Catholicism, the Habsburg state's official and majority religion. This stirred up controversy about whether she was forced, or whether a Muslim was even allowed to change her or his religion. Subsequent debates resulted in the Austrian Conversion Ordinance of 1891, which made religious conversion of subjects a matter of state. A strict procedure required the convert to be an adult and mentally healthy, and the conversion should be recognised by all parties involved; if not, the state would intervene and set up a commission for arbitration.<ref>Deringi (2012), p. 91–92.</ref>

In the 20th century, religion became highly politicised in Bosnia, and the basis for most citizens' national identity and political loyalty, leading to numerous conflicts culminating in the [[Bosnian War]] (1992–5). The resulting violence and misery has caused a group of Bosnians to reject religion (and nationalism) altogether. This atheist community faces discrimination, and is frequently verbally attacked by religious leaders as "corrupt people without morals".<ref>{{Cite book |last=Dubensky |first=Joyce S. |date=2016 |title=Peacemakers in Action: Profiles in Religious Peacebuilding |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=stb4DAAAQBAJ&pg=PA391 |location=Cambridge |publisher=Cambridge University Press |page=391 |isbn=9781107152960 |accessdate=4 January 2018}}</ref>

=== Brunei ===
{{Main|Freedom of religion in Brunei|Human rights in Brunei}}
{{See also|Religion in Brunei}}
[[Islam in Brunei|Brunei]] is the latest Muslim-majority country to enact a law that makes apostasy a crime punishable with death. In 2013, it enacted Syariah (Sharia) Penal Code. Section 112(1) of the new law states that a Muslim who declares himself non-Muslim commits a crime punishable with death, or with imprisonment for a term not exceeding thirty years, depending on evidence.<ref>[https://www.loc.gov/law/help/apostasy/index.php#brunei Brunei – Laws Criminalizing Apostasy] {{webarchive|url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20171231144725/https://www.loc.gov/law/help/apostasy/index.php |date=31 December 2017 }} Library of Congress (May 2014)</ref> Under the required wait period between notification of law and its validity under Brunei's constitution, its new apostasy law and corporal punishment will be applied starting October 2014, and capital punishment will be imposed starting October 2015.<ref>Rabiatul Kamit & Bandar Seri Begawan, Kedah Officials in Brunei to Observe Syariah Law, Brunei Times (16 May 2014)</ref>

=== Egypt ===
{{Main|Freedom of religion in Egypt|Human rights in Egypt}}
{{See also|Religion in Egypt}}

;Legal situation
[[File:A bittersweet release - Flickr - Al Jazeera English - cropped.jpg|thumb|[[Kareem Amer]], a few days after his release from 4 years in jail.<ref name="Reuters 24-10-2010">{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2010/11/24/egypt-blogger-idAFLDE6AN0ZR20101124 |title=Egypt blogger says jail won't stop future activism |author=Sarah Mikhail |work=Reuters |date=24 October 2010 |accessdate=14 September 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924150350/http://www.reuters.com/article/2010/11/24/egypt-blogger-idAFLDE6AN0ZR20101124 |archivedate=24 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>]]
[[File:Women in the revolution.jpg|thumb|Stencil graffiti depicting [[Aliaa Magda Elmahdy]], in the form of the nude blog photo of herself.]]
The [[Blasphemy law in Egypt|blasphemy law]]s and Article 98(f) of [[Egyptian Civil Code|Egyptian Penal Code]], as amended by Law 147, has been used to prosecute Muslims who have converted to [[Christianity in Egypt|Christianity]].<ref name=locegypt>[https://www.loc.gov/law/help/apostasy/index.php#egypt Egypt – Laws Criminalizing Apostasy] {{webarchive|url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20171231144725/https://www.loc.gov/law/help/apostasy/index.php |date=31 December 2017 }} Library of Congress (May 2014)</ref> For example, in May 2007, Bahaa El-Din El-Akkad, a former [[Islam in Egypt|Egyptian Muslim]] and someone who worked on [[Dawah]] to spread Islam, was imprisoned after he converted to Christianity, under the charge of "blasphemy against Islam". He was freed in 2011.<ref name=locegypt/>

Egypt's penal code is silent about any punishment for apostasy from Islam. Contemporary Egyptian jurisprudence prohibits apostasy from Islam, but has also remained silent about the death penalty.<ref name=mauritsberger/> Article 2 of the Constitution of Egypt enshrines sharia.<ref>[http://www.sis.gov.eg/Newvr/Dustor-en001.pdf Constitution of Egypt] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150718052913/http://www.sis.gov.eg/Newvr/Dustor-en001.pdf |date=18 July 2015 }} Unofficial Translation released by the Government of Egypt (2014)</ref> Both [[Judiciary of Egypt#Court|Court]] of Cassation and the Supreme Administrative Court of Egypt have ruled that, "it is completely acceptable for non-Muslims to embrace Islam but by consensus Muslims are not allowed to embrace another religion or to become of no religion at all [in Egypt]."<ref name=mauritsberger>Maurits S. Berger, Apostasy and Public Policy in Contemporary Egypt: An Evaluation of Recent Cases from Egypt's Highest Courts, Human Rights Quarterly, Vol. 25, pp. 720–40</ref> The silence about punishment for apostasy along with the constitutional enshrinement of Sharia, means the death sentence for apostasy is a possibility. In practice, Egypt has prosecuted apostasy from Islam under its blasphemy laws using the Hisbah doctrine;<ref>S. Olsson (2008), Apostasy in Egypt: Contemporary Cases of Ḥisbah, The Muslim World, 98(1): 95– 115</ref> and non-state Islamic groups have taken the law into their own hands and executed apostates.<ref name=farajfawda/>

A 2010 Pew Research Center poll showed that 84% of Egyptian Muslims believe those who leave Islam should be punished by death.<ref name="pewglobal.org">{{cite web |url=http://www.pewglobal.org/files/2010/12/Pew-Global-Attitudes-Muslim-Report-FINAL-December-2-2010.pdf |title=Global Attitudes Project : Muslim Publics Divided on Hamas and Hezbollah |publisher=Pewglobal.org |accessdate=2013-11-29 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140228192924/http://pewglobal.org/files/2010/12/Pew-Global-Attitudes-Muslim-Report-FINAL-December-2-2010.pdf |archivedate=28 February 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

;Cases and incidents
In 1992, [[Islamist]] militants gunned down [[Secularism in Egypt|Egyptian secularist]] and [[Sharia#Criticism|sharia law opponent]] [[Farag Foda]]. Before his death he had been declared an apostate and foe of Islam by the ulama at [[Al Azhar]]. During the trial of the murderers, Al-Azhar scholar [[Mohammed al-Ghazali]] testified that when the state fails to punish apostates, somebody else has to do it.<ref name=farajfawda>{{cite web|url=http://www.gloria-center.org/2007/06/soage-2007-06-03/ |title=Faraj Fawda, or the Cost of Freedom of Expression |publisher=Meria.idc.ac.il |accessdate=2014-07-23 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100527144144/http://meria.idc.ac.il/journal/2007/issue2/jv11no2a3.html |archivedate=27 May 2010 |deadurl=yes |df=dmy }}</ref>

In 1993, a [[Liberal Muslim movements|liberal Islamic]] [[Schools of Islamic theology|theologian]], [[Nasr Abu Zayd]] was denied promotion at [[Cairo University]] after a court decision of apostasy against him.  Following this an Islamist lawyer filed a lawsuit before the Giza Lower Personal Status Court demanding the [[Divorce in Islam|divorce]] of Abu Zayd from his wife, Dr. Ibtihal Younis, on the grounds that a Muslim woman cannot be married to an apostate – notwithstanding the fact his wife wished to remain married to him. The case went to the Cairo Appeals Court where his marriage was declared null and void in 1995.<ref name="obit-abuzaid">[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/professor-nasr-hamed-abu-zaid-modernist-islamic-philosopher-who-was-forced-into-exile-by-fundamentalists-2025754.html Professor Nasr Hamed Abu Zaid: Modernist islamic philosopher who was forced into exile by fundamentalists ] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925115825/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/professor-nasr-hamed-abu-zaid-modernist-islamic-philosopher-who-was-forced-into-exile-by-fundamentalists-2025754.html |date=25 September 2015 }}|By Adel Darwish | 14 July 2010 |The Independent</ref> After the verdict, the [[Egyptian Islamic Jihad]] organization (which had assassinated Egyptian president [[Anwar Sadat]] in 1981) declared Abu Zayd should be killed for abandoning his Muslim faith. Abu Zayd was given police protection, but felt he could not function under heavy guard, noting that one police guard referred to him as "the kafir".<ref>[http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/2000/486/eg6.htm When the professor can't teach] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090716051140/http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/2000/486/eg6.htm |date=16 July 2009 }}| Al Ahram| By Nadia Abou El-Magd |15–21 June 2000</ref> On 23 July 1995, he and his wife flew to Europe, where they lived in exile but continued to teach.<ref name="obit-abuzaid"/>

In April 2006, after a [[Persecution of Bahá'ís#Egypt|court case in Egypt recognized]] the [[Bahá'í Faith]], members of the clergy convinced the government to appeal the court decision. One member of parliament, Gamal Akl of the opposition Muslim Brotherhood, said the Bahá'ís were infidels who should be killed on the grounds that they had changed their religion, this despite the fact that most living Bahá'í have not, in fact, ever been Muslim.<ref>{{Cite news|agency=[[Reuters]] |date=3 May 2006 |title=State to appeal ruling that favours Egypt's Baha'is |url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/DisplayArticle.asp?xfile=data/middleeast/2006/May/middleeast_May69.xml&section=middleeast&col= |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110608131200/http://www.khaleejtimes.com/DisplayArticle.asp?xfile=data%2Fmiddleeast%2F2006%2FMay%2Fmiddleeast_May69.xml&section=middleeast&col= |archivedate=8 June 2011 |work=[[Khaleej Times]] |accessdate=15 October 2009 |deadurl=yes }}</ref>

In October 2006, [[Kareem Amer]] became the first Egyptian to be prosecuted for their online writings, including declaring himself an atheist. He was imprisoned until November 2010.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.atlantico.fr/rdv/revue-blogs/aliaa-egyptienne-qui-provoque-etat-islamique-1720237.html |title=Aliaa, l'Egyptienne qui provoque l'Etat islamique |author=Claire Ulrich |work=Atlantico |date=26 August 2014 |accessdate=14 September 2017 |language=fr |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170909233843/http://www.atlantico.fr/rdv/revue-blogs/aliaa-egyptienne-qui-provoque-etat-islamique-1720237.html |archivedate=9 September 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

In 2007 [[Mohammed Hegazy]], a Muslim-born Egyptian who had converted to Christianity based on "readings and comparative studies in religions", sued the Egyptian court to change his religion from "Islam" to "Christianity" on his national identification card.  His case caused considerable public uproar,  with not only Muslim clerics, but his own father and wife's father calling for his death. Two lawyers he had hired or agreed to hire both quit his case, and two Christian human rights workers thought to be involved in his case were arrested. As of 2007, he and his wife were in hiding. In 2008, the judge trying his case ruled that according to sharia, Islam is the final and most complete religion and therefore Muslims already practice full freedom of religion and cannot convert to an older belief.<ref name=KUWAIT>{{cite web|title=Egyptian Christian convert goes into hiding amid death threats |publisher=Kuwait Times |url=http://www.kuwaittimes.net/read_news.php?newsid=MTAxNzY2OTk2MA== |date=2007-08-11 |accessdate=2007-08-11 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070901194650/http://www.kuwaittimes.net/read_news.php?newsid=MTAxNzY2OTk2MA%3D%3D |archivedate=1 September 2007 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref name=IHT>{{cite news | title = Muslim converts to Christianity foments sectarian antagonism | agency = Associated Press | date = 2007-08-11 | accessdate = 2007-08-11 | url = http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2007/08/11/africa/ME-GEN-Egypt-Muslim-Convert.php | publisher = International Herald Tribune | deadurl = no | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070814230341/http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2007/08/11/africa/ME-GEN-Egypt-Muslim-Convert.php | archivedate = 14 August 2007 | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.christianpost.com/article/20080203/egypt-rules-christian-convert-must-remain-legally-muslim/index.html |title=Egypt Rules Christian Convert Must Remain Legally Muslim |work=The Christian Post |date=3 February 2008 |accessdate=2010-04-29 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://swap.stanford.edu/20100118204943/http://www.christianpost.com/article/20080203/egypt%2Drules%2Dchristian%2Dconvert%2Dmust%2Dremain%2Dlegally%2Dmuslim/index.html |archivedate=18 January 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Hegazy kept trying to officially change his religion until he was arrested in 2013 for "spreading false rumours and incitement". He was released in 2016, after which he published a video on YouTube claiming he had reverted to Islam, and asked to be left alone.<ref name="Samuel">{{Cite news |url=https://www.groene.nl/artikel/mohammed-gelooft-niet-meer-in-god |title=Mohammed gelooft niet meer in God |author=Mounir Samuel |work=De Groene Amsterdammer |date=10 January 2018 |accessdate=15 January 2018 |language=nl |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180113133041/https://www.groene.nl/artikel/mohammed-gelooft-niet-meer-in-god |archivedate=13 January 2018 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

In February 2009, another case of a convert to Christianity (Maher Ahmad El-Mo'otahssem Bellah El-Gohary), came to court. El-Gohary's effort to officially convert to Christianity triggered state prosecutors charging him of "apostasy," or leaving Islam, and seeking a sentence of death penalty.

{{quote|"Our rights in Egypt, as Christians or converts, are less than the rights of animals," El-Gohary said. "We are deprived of social and civil rights, deprived of our inheritance and left to the fundamentalists to be killed. Nobody bothers to investigate or care about us." El-Gohary, 56, has been attacked in the street, spat at and knocked down in his effort to win the right to officially convert. He said he and his 14-year-old daughter continue to receive death threats by text message and phone call.<ref>{{Cite news |author=Compass Direct |date=26 February 2009 |title=Egyptian Islamic Lawyers Urge Death Sentence For Convert |url=http://www.aina.org/news/20090226172430.htm |publisher=[[Assyrian International News Agency]] |accessdate=15 October 2009 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110613220219/http://www.aina.org/news/20090226172430.htm |archivedate=13 June 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>}}

Some commentators have reported a growing trend of abandoning religion following the Egyptian Revolution of 2011, reflected through emergence of support groups on social media, although openly declared apostates still face ostracism and danger of prosecution and vigilante violence.<ref>{{cite news|title=Invisible Atheists|author=Ahmed Benchems|date=23 April 2015|newspaper=New Republic|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/121559/rise-arab-atheists|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170930012014/https://newrepublic.com/article/121559/rise-arab-atheists|archivedate=30 September 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Egypt's atheists find each other on social media|author=Enas Hamed|url=http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2014/05/atheism-egypt-criticism-law.html|newspaper=Al-Monitor|date=May 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170211235559/http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2014/05/atheism-egypt-criticism-law.html|archivedate=11 February 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> A well-known example is the Internet activist [[Aliaa Magda Elmahdy]] (then-girlfriend of Kareem Amer), who protested the oppression of women's rights and sexuality in Islam by posting a nude photo of herself online.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/11/19/world/meast/nude-blogger-aliaa-magda-elmahdy/index.html |title=Egyptian blogger Aliaa Elmahdy: Why I posed naked |author=Mohamed Fadel Fahmy |work=CCN |publisher= |date=20 November 2011 |accessdate=14 September 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170914035348/http://edition.cnn.com/2011/11/19/world/meast/nude-blogger-aliaa-magda-elmahdy/index.html |archivedate=14 September 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 2011, the Muslim woman Abeer allegedly converted to Christianity, and was given protection by the [[Church of Saint Menas (Cairo)|Church of Saint Menas]] in [[Imbaba]]. Hundreds of angry salafists beleaguered the church and demanded her return; during the resulting clashes, ten people were killed and hundreds were wounded.<ref name="Samuel"/>

[[File:Ahmed Harkan.png|thumb|Activist [[Ahmed Harqan]]'s televised debates attracted hostility.]]
On 21 October 2014, ex-Muslim atheist activist [[Ahmed Harqan]] featured in a debate on the popular Egyptian talk show ''Taht al Koubry'' ("Under the Bridge"). He explained why he had become an atheist and said that Islam is a "harsh religion", which was being implemented by [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]] (ISIS) and [[Boko Haram]]. They are doing "what the Prophet Muhammad and his companions did," said Harqan.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.memri.org/tv/egyptian-human-rights-activist-ahmad-harqan-isis-doing-what-prophet-muhammad-did |title=Egyptian Human Rights Activist Ahmad Harqan: ISIS Is Doing what the Prophet Muhammad Did |publisher=Middle East Media Research Institute |date=21 October 2014 |accessdate=6 March 2018 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180307082357/https://www.memri.org/tv/egyptian-human-rights-activist-ahmad-harqan-isis-doing-what-prophet-muhammad-did |archivedate=7 March 2018 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Four days later, in the evening of 25 October, he and his pregnant wife Nada Mandour (Saly) Harqan (also an atheist), were attacked by a lynch mob and escaped assassination when they fled to a nearby police station.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=siHKC0tQNKI |title=Atheist Egyptian couple escape a lynch mob, only to be beaten by the police |work=Dotmsr |date=8 December 2014 |accessdate=6 March 2018}}</ref> Instead of taking action to help Harqan and his wife, the police officers further assaulted them and they were imprisoned, charged with blasphemy and "defamation of religion" under [[Blasphemy law in Egypt|article 98 in the Egyptian penal code]] for asking "What has ISIS done that Muhammad did not do?" on the talk show. Harqan's appearance provoked weeks of outcry from Islamic religious broadcasters and prompted much-watched follow-up shows.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/09/world/europe/raising-questions-within-islam-after-france-shooting.html|title=Raising Questions Within Islam After France Shooting|author=David D. Kirkpatrick|date=8 January 2015|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=12 January 2015|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150111220103/http://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/09/world/europe/raising-questions-within-islam-after-france-shooting.html|archivedate=11 January 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 3 November 2015, Harqan was invited to debate on Al-Assema TV, where he got into an argument with the host, Rania Mahmoud Yassin (daughter of actor [[Mahmoud Yacine]]), whom he claimed was not objective and fair. The discussion barely focused on religion itself, and mainly about Harqan's claim that in a debate the host should be [[Impartiality|impartial]] to ensure a balanced exchange. However, Yassin maintained an anti-atheist position and said that they had only invited Harqan on the show "so that people can learn a lesson from atheism, heresy, and all those disgraceful phenomena in society", whereupon Harqan stood up and left the show in protest.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.memri.org/tv/tv-host-clashes-egyptian-atheist-live-air-we-dont-want-infidels-here/ |title=TV Host Clashes with Egyptian Atheist Live on the Air: We Don't Want Infidels Here |publisher=Middle East Media Research Institute |date=3 November 2015 |accessdate=6 March 2018 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180307023257/https://www.memri.org/tv/tv-host-clashes-egyptian-atheist-live-air-we-dont-want-infidels-here/ |archivedate=7 March 2018 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

=== Indonesia ===
{{Main|Blasphemy law in Indonesia|Freedom of religion in Indonesia|Human rights in Indonesia}}
{{See also|Religion in Indonesia}}
[[File:Soegijapranata Nasional 8 Nov 1960 p1.jpg|thumb|[[Albertus Soegijapranata]], an [[List of former Muslims|ex-Muslim]] and a [[National Hero of Indonesia|national hero of Indonesia]], was the first [[native Indonesian]] [[Catholic]] bishop.]]
[[Islam in Indonesia|Indonesia]] does not have a [[Law of Indonesia|law]] against apostasy, and [[Constitution of Indonesia|the constitution]] provides for freedom of religion, accords "all persons shall be free to choose and to practice the religion of his/her choice".<ref>{{cite web | title = The 1945 Constitution of the Republic of Indonesia | url = http://www.us-asean.org/Indonesia/constitution.htm | accessdate = 2 October 2006 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070310160936/http://www.us-asean.org/Indonesia/constitution.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 10 March 2007}}</ref> But Indonesia has as a broad blasphemy law that protects all six official religions ([[Islam]], [[Protestantism]], [[Catholicism]], [[Hinduism]], [[Buddhism]] and [[Confucianism]]) (Article 156) and a Presidential Decree (1965) that permits prosecution of people who commit blasphemy.<ref>[https://www.loc.gov/law/help/apostasy/index.php#indonesia Indonesia - Laws Criminalizing Apostasy] {{webarchive|url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20171231144725/https://www.loc.gov/law/help/apostasy/index.php |date=31 December 2017 }} Library of Congress (May 2014)</ref> The Decree prohibits every Indonesian from "intentionally conveying, endorsing or attempting to gain public support in the interpretation of a certain religion; or undertaking religious based activities that resemble the religious activities of the religion in question, where such interpretation and activities are in deviation of the basic teachings of the religion."<ref>Jo-Anne Prud'homme, [http://www.freedomhouse.org/sites/default/files/PolicingBelief_ Indonesia.pdf  Policing Belief: The Impact of Blasphemy Laws], Human Rights 46, Freedom House, (Oct. 2010).</ref> These laws have been used to arrest and convict atheist apostates in Indonesia, such as the case of 30-year old [[Alexander Aan]] who declared himself to be an atheist, declared "God does not exist", and stopped praying and fasting as required by Islam. He received death threats from Islamic groups and in 2012 was arrested and sentenced to two and a half years in prison.<ref>[http://interfidei.or.id/index.php?page=news&id=100&lang=en Islam, Pancasila and Atheism] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140903081354/http://interfidei.or.id/index.php?page=news&id=100&lang=en |date=3 September 2014 }} M. Syafi'i Anwar, Sajian Utama, Institut DIAN, Yogyakarta, Indonesia (26 June 2012)</ref><ref>[http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2012/06/18/commentary-is-there-room-atheists-indonesia.html Is there room for atheists in Indonesia] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120926124025/http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2012/06/18/commentary-is-there-room-atheists-indonesia.html |date=26 September 2012 }} Endy Bayuni, The Jakarta Post, Indonesia (18 June 2012)</ref>

=== Iran ===
[[File:Salman Rushdie 2012 Shankbone-2.jpg|thumb|[[Salman Rushdie]], [[The Satanic Verses controversy|targeted by Iran's ayatollah]] with a death sentence.]]
{{Main|Freedom of religion in Iran|Human rights in Iran|Blasphemy law in Iran|Capital punishment in Iran}}
{{See also|Islamization of Iran|Religion in Iran}}
The [[1988 executions of Iranian political prisoners]], starting near the end of the [[Iran–Iraq War]] (1980–1988), were carried out by "Special Commissions with instructions to execute members of [[People's Mojahedin Organization of Iran]] as ''[[Moharebeh|moharebs]]'' (those who war against [[Allah]]) and [[leftist]]s as ''mortads'' (apostates from Islam)."<ref name="Abrahamian, Ervand 1999, p.210">Abrahamian, Ervand, ''Tortured Confessions'', University of California Press, 1999, p. 210.</ref> It is unclear how many prisoners were killed (estimates vary from almost 4,500<ref name="amnesty">{{cite web |url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/documents/mde13/021/1990/en/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-08-07 |df= }}</ref> to more than 30,000<ref name="Lamb">{{Cite news|last=Lamb|first=Christina|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/iran/1321090/Khomeini-fatwa-led-to-killing-of-30000-in-Iran.html|title=Khomeini fatwa 'led to killing of 30,000 in Iran'|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=2001-02-04|accessdate=2017-06-23|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170701102148/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/iran/1321090/Khomeini-fatwa-led-to-killing-of-30000-in-Iran.html|archivedate=1 July 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>), how many of them actually were ex-Muslims or were falsely accused of having left Islam, and the exact motivations behind this massacre. Great care was taken to keep the killings undercover, and the government of Iran currently denies their having taken place. Justifications offered for the alleged executions vary, but one of the most common theories advanced is that they were in retaliation for the 1988 [[Operation Mersad|attack]] on the western borders of Iran by the PMOI Mujahedin. However, this does not fully account for the targeting of other [[leftist]] groups who opposed the Mujahedin invasion.<ref>Abrahamian, ''Tortured Confessions'', (1999), 218</ref>

[[Salman Rushdie]] is a prominent<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6756149.stm |publisher=BBC News |title=15 June 2007 Rushdie knighted in honours list |accessdate=2007-06-16 |date=15 June 2007 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070823004356/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6756149.stm |archivedate=23 August 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> contemporary figure accused of apostasy. In 1989 a fatwa was issued by [[Ayatollah Khomeini]], the ruler of Iran at the time, calling for the death of Salman Rushdie for the blasphemy of authoring the book ''[[The Satanic Verses controversy|The Satanic Verses]]''.

Hossein Soodmand, who converted from Islam to [[Christianity in Iran|Christianity]] when he was 13 years old, was [[Capital punishment in Iran|executed]] by [[Hanging#Iran|hanging]] in 1990 for apostasy.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/iran/3179465/Hanged-for-being-a-Christian-in-Iran.html |title=Hanged for being a Christian in Iran |publisher=Telegraph |date=2008-10-11 |accessdate=2015-01-15 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150204131649/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/iran/3179465/Hanged-for-being-a-Christian-in-Iran.html |archivedate=4 February 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

According to US think tank [[Freedom House]], since the 1990s the Islamic Republic of Iran has sometimes used [[Death squad#Iran|death squad]]s against converts, including major Protestant leaders. Under President [[Mahmoud Ahmadinejad]], the regime has engaged in a systematic campaign to track down and reconvert or kill those who have changed their religion from Islam.<ref name=marshall20080410/>

15 ex-Muslim Christians<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20180321063237/http://compassdirect.org/en/display.php?page=breaking&lang=en&length=long&idelement=5470 <!-- |accessdate=12 July 2008 --> ]</ref> were incarcerated on 15 May 2008 under charges of apostasy.  They may face the death penalty if convicted.  A new penal code is being proposed in Iran that would require the death penalty in cases of apostasy on the Internet.<ref>{{Cite news |date=2 July 2008 |title=Iran considering death penalty for web-related crimes |url=http://gulfnews.com/news/region/iran/iran-considering-death-penalty-for-web-related-crimes-1.116338 |work=[[Gulf News]] |accessdate=15 October 2009 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110411195502/http://gulfnews.com/news/region/iran/iran-considering-death-penalty-for-web-related-crimes-1.116338 |archivedate=11 April 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>
[[File:Should We Leave Islam - Armin Navabi.webm|thumb|left|Ex-Muslim [[Armin Navabi]], founder of [[Atheist Republic]], escaped Iran.]]
At least two Iranians – [[Hashem Aghajari]] and [[Hassan Youssefi Eshkevari]] – have been arrested and charged with apostasy in the Islamic Republic (though not executed), not for self-professed conversion to another faith, but for statements and/or activities deemed by courts of the Islamic Republic to be in violation of Islam, and that appear to outsiders to be Islamic reformist political expression.<ref>{{Cite news |date=7 November 2002 |title=Iranian academic sentenced to death |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/2415751.stm |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=15 October 2009 |first=Jim |last=Muir |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090103124037/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/2415751.stm |archivedate=3 January 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[Hashem Aghajari]], was found guilty of apostasy for a speech urging Iranians to "not blindly follow" Islamic clerics;<ref>{{cite press release |title=Iran: Academic's Death Sentence Condemned |publisher=[[Human Rights Watch]] |date=9 November 2002 |url=https://www.hrw.org/press/2002/11/iranacademic.htm |archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20021113145848/http://hrw.org/press/2002/11/iranacademic.htm |archivedate=13 November 2002 |accessdate=15 October 2009}}</ref> Hassan Youssefi Eshkevari was charged with apostasy for attending the [['Iran After the Elections' Conference]] in Berlin Germany which was disrupted by anti-regime demonstrators.<ref name="ITFCA">{{cite press release |title=Iran: Trial for Conference Attendees |publisher=[[Human Rights Watch]] |date=1 November 2000 |url=https://www.hrw.org/en/news/2000/11/01/iran-trial-conference-attendees |accessdate=15 October 2009 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090730092138/http://www.hrw.org/en/news/2000/11/01/iran-trial-conference-attendees |archivedate=30 July 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

The [[Bahá'í Faith in Iran|Bahá'ís in Iran]], the nation of origin of the Bahá'í Faith and Iran's largest religious minority, were [[Persecution of Bahá'ís#Iran|accused of apostasy]] in the 19th century by the Shi'a clergy because of their adherence to religious revelations by another prophet after those of Muhammad. These allegations led to mob attacks, public executions and torture of early Bahais, including the [[Báb]].<ref>{{Cite journal|first=Friedrich W. |last=Affolter |title=The Specter of Ideological Genocide: The Bahá'ís of Iran |journal=War Crimes, Genocide and Crimes Against Humanity |volume=1 |issue=1 |pages=59–89 |date=January 2005 |url=http://www.altoona.psu.edu/journals/war-crimes/articles/V1/v1n1a3.pdf |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120722083412/http://www.altoona.psu.edu/journals/war-crimes/articles/V1/v1n1a3.pdf |archivedate=22 July 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> More recently, Musa Talibi was arrested in 1994, and [[Dhabihu'llah Mahrami]] was arrested in 1995, then sentenced to death on charges of apostasy.<ref>{{cite book | title = U.S. Condemns Iran's Persecution of Bahai Religious Prisoner | publisher = U.S. Department of State | author = Bureau of International Information Programs | url = http://www.iranhrdc.org/english/human-rights-documents/aadel-collection/12398-u-s-comdemns-iran-s-persecution-of-bahai-religious-prisoner.html | deadurl = no | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20151117152909/http://www.iranhrdc.org/english/human-rights-documents/aadel-collection/12398-u-s-comdemns-iran-s-persecution-of-bahai-religious-prisoner.html | archivedate = 17 November 2015 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>

In July 2017, an activist group that spread atheistic articles and books Iranian universities, published a video on YouTube titled "Why we must deny the existence of God", featuring famous atheist thinkers Richard Dawkins, Sam Harris, Christopher Hitchens and Daniel Dennett. An hour before the group would meet to discuss the production of a new video, their office was raided by the police. Group member Keyvan (32), raised as a Sunni Muslim but confusingly educated in a Shia school, long had doubts about religion, and became an apostate after reading atheist literature. He and his wife had to flee after the police raid, and flew to the Netherlands three days later.<ref name="Breggen">{{Cite news |url=https://www.trouw.nl/religie-en-filosofie/alleen-in-stilte-kun-je-ex-moslim-zijn~a507d176/ |title=Alleen in stilte kun je ex-moslim zijn |author=Marinde van der Breggen |work=Trouw |date=5 December 2017 |accessdate=8 December 2017 |language=nl |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171208174754/https://www.trouw.nl/religie-en-filosofie/alleen-in-stilte-kun-je-ex-moslim-zijn~a507d176/ |archivedate=8 December 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

=== Iraq ===
[[File:Faisal Saeed al Mutar SASHAcon 2014.jpg|thumb|Ex-Muslim [[Faisal Saeed al Mutar]], founder of Global Secular Humanist Movement (2010), fled Iraq in 2013.]]
{{main|Freedom of religion in Iraq}}
{{See also|Religion in Iraq}}
Although the Constitution of Iraq recognizes [[Islam]] as the official religion and states that no law may be enacted that contradicts the established provisions of Islam, it also guarantees freedom of thought, conscience, and religious belief and practice. While the Government generally endorses these rights, unsettled conditions have prevented effective governance in parts of the country, and the Government's ability to protect religious freedoms has been handicapped by insurgency, terrorism, and [[sectarian]] violence. Since 2003, when the government of [[Saddam Hussein]] fell, the Iraqi government has generally not engaged in state-sponsored persecution of any religious group, calling instead for tolerance and acceptance of all religious minorities.

In October 2013, 15-year-old Ahmad Sherwan from Erbil said he no longer believed in God and was proud to be an atheist to his father, who had the police arrest him. He was imprisoned for 13 days and tortured several times, before being released on bail; he faced life imprisonment for disbelief in God. Sherwan tried to contact the media for seven months, but all refused to run his story until the private newspaper ''Awene'' published it in May 2014. It went viral, and human rights activists came to his aid.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.yourmiddleeast.com/culture/interview-with-persecuted-young-atheist-in-erbil_23918 |title=Interview with persecuted young atheist in Erbil |author=Rozh Ahmad |work=Your Middle East |date=28 May 2014 |accessdate=13 September 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170913232600/http://www.yourmiddleeast.com/culture/interview-with-persecuted-young-atheist-in-erbil_23918 |archivedate=13 September 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

The 2014 uprising of the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]] (IS or ISIS) has led to violations of religious freedom in certain parts of Iraq.<ref name="Arabic CNN">{{cite web|url=http://arabic.cnn.com/middleeast/2014/06/29/urgent-isis-declares-caliphate|title=داعش تعلن تأسيس دولة الخلافة وتسميتها "الدولة الإسلامية" فقط دون العراق والشام والبغدادي أميرها وتحذر "لا عذر لمن يتخلف عن البيعة|publisher=Arabic CNN|date=29 June 2014|accessdate=31 July 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140726174108/http://arabic.cnn.com/middleeast/2014/06/29/urgent-isis-declares-caliphate|archivedate=26 July 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ISIS follows an extreme anti-Western interpretation of Islam, promotes religious violence and regards those who do not agree with its interpretations as infidels or apostates.<ref name="NS">{{cite news|title=Islamic State|url=http://www.nationalsecurity.gov.au/Listedterroristorganisations/Pages/IslamicState.aspx|accessdate=22 July 2014|work=Australian National Security|agency=Australian Government|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808170809/http://www.nationalsecurity.gov.au/Listedterroristorganisations/Pages/IslamicState.aspx|archivedate=8 August 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

{{Quote box
|class = letterhead
|title =
|tstyle = text-align: right;
|title_bg = none
|border=none
|quote = Islam has given me nothing,<br /> no respect, no rights as a woman.
|source = – Huda Mohammed<ref name="Neurink"/>
|qalign = right
}}

In the 2010s, an increasing number of Iraqis, especially young people in the capital city of [[Baghdad]] and the [[Kurdistan Region]], were leaving Islam for a variety of reasons. Some cite the lack of women's rights in Islam, others the political climate, which is dominated by conflicts between Shia Muslim parties who seek to expand their power more than they try to improve citizens' living conditions. Many young ex-Muslims sought refuge in the [[Iraqi Communist Party]], and advocated for secularism from within its ranks. The sale of books on atheism by authors such as [[Abdullah al-Qasemi]] and [[Richard Dawkins]] has risen in Baghdad. In Iraqi Kurdistan, a 2011 AK-News survey asking whether respondents believed God existed, resulted in 67% replying 'yes', 21% 'probably', 4% 'probably not', 7% 'no' and 1% had no answer. The subsequent harsh battle against Islamic State and its literalist implementation of Sharia caused numerous youths to dissociate themselves from Islam altogether, either by adopting [[Zoroastrianism]] or secretly embracing atheism.<ref name="Neurink">{{Cite news |url=https://www.trouw.nl/religie-en-filosofie/in-irak-keren-jongeren-de-islam-de-rug-toe~ab5f8303/ |title=In Irak keren jongeren de islam de rug toe |author=Judit Neurink |work=[[Trouw]] |date=12 September 2017 |accessdate=13 September 2017 |language=nl |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912193738/https://www.trouw.nl/religie-en-filosofie/in-irak-keren-jongeren-de-islam-de-rug-toe~ab5f8303/ |archivedate=12 September 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

When Sadr al-Din learned about [[natural selection]] in school, he began questioning the [[Islamic attitudes towards science|relationship between Islam and science]], studying the history of Islam, and asking people's opinions on both topics. At the age of 20, he changed his first name to Daniel, after atheist philosopher [[Daniel Dennett]]. He came into conflict with his family, who threatened him with death, and after his father found books in his room denying the existence of God and miracles, he tried to shoot his son. Daniel fled Iraq, and obtained asylum in the Netherlands.<ref name="Breggen"/>

=== Jordan ===
[[File:Mohammed AlKhadra speech.webm|thumb|Jordanian Atheists Group founder Mohammed AlKhadra encouraging ex-Muslims to be 'out, loud and proud'.]]
{{Main|Freedom of religion in Jordan|Human rights in Jordan|Blasphemy law in Jordan|Capital punishment in Jordan}}
{{See also|Religion in Jordan}}
[[Islam in Jordan]] does not explicitly ban apostasy in its penal code; however, it permits any Jordanian to charge another with apostasy and its Islamic courts to consider conversion trials.<ref>[https://www.loc.gov/law/help/apostasy/index.php#jordan Jordan –  Laws Criminalizing Apostasy] {{webarchive|url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20171231144725/https://www.loc.gov/law/help/apostasy/index.php |date=31 December 2017 }} Library of Congress (May 2014)</ref> If an Islamic court convicts a person of apostasy, it has the power to sentence a prison term, annul that person's marriage, seize property and disqualify him or her from inheritance rights. The Jordanian poet Islam Samhan was accused of apostasy for poems he wrote in 2008, and sentenced to a prison term in 2009.<ref>[http://www.thenational.ae/news/world/middle-east/jordanian-poet-prepares-for-jail Jordanian poet prepares for jail] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140903063209/http://www.thenational.ae/news/world/middle-east/jordanian-poet-prepares-for-jail |date=3 September 2014 }} The National, UAE (2 September 2009)</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/books/2008/oct/24/poet-jordan-arrest-quran-islam Jordan arrests poet for insulting Islam] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170102115107/https://www.theguardian.com/books/2008/oct/24/poet-jordan-arrest-quran-islam |date=2 January 2017 }} The Guardian (24 October 2008)</ref>

=== Kosovo ===
{{Main|Religion in Kosovo}}
;Crypto-Catholics
[[Kosovo]] was conquered by the [[Ottoman Empire]] along with the other [[Fall of the Serbian Empire|remnants of the Serbian Empire]] in the period following the [[Battle of Kosovo]] (1389). Although the Ottomans didn't force the Catholic and Orthodox Christian population to convert to Islam, there was strong social pressure (such as not having to pay the [[jizya]]) as well as political expediency to do so, which ethnic Albanians did in far greater numbers (including the entire nobility) than Serbs, Greeks and others in the region.<ref>Encarta-encyclopedie Winkler Prins (1993–2002) s.v. "Albanië. §6. Geschiedenis". Microsoft Corporation/Het Spectrum.</ref> Many Albanian Catholics converted to Islam in the 17th and 18th centuries, despite attempts by Roman Catholic clergy to stop them, including a strict condemnation of conversion – especially for opportunistic reasons such as jizya evasion – during the ''Concilium Albanicum'', a meeting of Albanian bishops in 1703. Whilst many of these converts stayed crypto-Catholics to a certain extent, often helped by pragmatic lower clerics, the higher Catholic clergy ordered them to be denied [[Sacraments of the Catholic Church|the sacraments]] for their heresy.<ref name="Duijzings 2000 86–99"/> Efforts to convert the [[Laramans|laraman community]] of [[Vitina|Letnica]] back to Catholicism began in 1837, but the effort was violently suppressed – the local Ottoman governor put laramans in jail.{{sfn|Duijzings|2000|p=92}} After the Ottoman Empire abolished the death penalty for apostasy from Islam by the [[Edict of Toleration 1844]], several groups of crypto-Catholics in [[Prizren]], [[Peć|Peja]] and [[Gjakova]] were recognised as Catholics by the Ottoman Grand Vizier in 1845. When the laramans of Letnica asked the district governor and judge in [[Gjilan]] to recognise them as Catholics, they were refused however, and subsequently imprisoned, and then deported to [[Anatolia]],{{sfn|Duijzings|2000|p=93}} from where they returned in November 1848 following diplomatic intervention.{{sfn|Duijzings|2000|p=94}} In 1856, a further [[Tanzimat]] [[Ottoman Reform Edict of 1856|reform]] improved the situation, and no further serious abuse was reported.{{sfn|Duijzings|2000|p=96}} The bulk of conversion of laramans, almost exclusively newly-borns, took place between 1872 and 1924.{{sfn|Duijzings|2000|p=99}}

=== Kuwait ===
{{Main|Freedom of religion in Kuwait|Human rights in Kuwait|Blasphemy law in Kuwait}}
{{See also|Islamization of Kuwait|Religion in Kuwait}}
According to a 2002 journal paper, Kuwait does not have a law that criminalizes apostasy.<ref name=ausgov>{{cite web|url=http://www.refworld.org/pdfid/4e6dee022.pdf|title=Country Advice Kuwait|publisher=Australian Government|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924125054/http://www.refworld.org/pdfid/4e6dee022.pdf|archivedate=24 September 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In practice, Kuwait's [[family law]] prosecutes apostates.<ref name=amnesty2>{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/download/Documents/172000/mde170051996en.pdf|title=Kuwait – Hussein Qambar 'Ali: Death threats|publisher=Amnesty International|pages=2–3|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150912091741/https://www.amnesty.org/download/Documents/172000/mde170051996en.pdf|archivedate=12 September 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> If an Islamic family court convicts a Muslim of apostasy, the court has the power to annul that person's marriage and disqualify him/her from property and inheritance rights.<ref>Ahmed Al-Suwei Shleibik (2009), Real Punishment of The Apostate, Journal of Sharia and Islamic Studies, 24(78)</ref><ref>[https://www.loc.gov/law/help/apostasy/index.php#kuwait Kuwait –  Laws Criminalizing Apostasy] {{webarchive|url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20171231144725/https://www.loc.gov/law/help/apostasy/index.php |date=31 December 2017 }} Library of Congress (May 2014)</ref> For example, the prosecution of Hussein Qambar Ali in an Islamic family court, on charges of apostasy, after he converted from Islam to Christianity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.refworld.org/docid/3ae6a9fc54.html|title=Amnesty International Report 1997 – Kuwait|publisher=Amnesty International|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924112151/http://www.refworld.org/docid/3ae6a9fc54.html|archivedate=24 September 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>Ben Clarke (2008), Ideological Extremism and the Abuse of Religion: 'Punishment of Apostasy' as a Rationale for Religious Violence by State and Non-State Actors, Law Conference Papers, Al-Hussein Bin Talal University, Ma'an Jordan, 10–13 July 2008</ref> Theoretically, death penalty can also be pronounced.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://en.qantara.de/content/atheism-in-the-arab-world-the-dictators-scourge-of-heresy-and-humanists |title=Atheism in the Arab World. The dictators' scourge: Of 'heresy' and humanists |publisher=Qantara.de |date=13 September 2017 |accessdate=15 September 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170914085247/https://en.qantara.de/content/atheism-in-the-arab-world-the-dictators-scourge-of-heresy-and-humanists |archivedate=14 September 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

Blasphemy is criminalized. Law 111 of Kuwait's Penal Code allows usage of statements posted on internet as evidence of blasphemy.<ref>[http://www.kuna.net.kw/ArticleDetails.aspx?id=2269659&language=ar Law 19 of 2012] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140903082115/http://www.kuna.net.kw/ArticleDetails.aspx?id=2269659&language=ar |date=3 September 2014 }}, al Jarida al Rasmiyya, Vol. 1102, Kuwait, 21 October 2012</ref>

=== Libya ===
[[File:Magdulien Abaida Secular Conference 2015.webm|thumb|Magdulien Abaida, Libyan human rights activist<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-20584573 |title=Libya rebel flees to UK as revolution sours for women |author=Tim Whewell |work=BBC Newsnight |date=4 December 2012 |accessdate=18 September 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170918124259/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-20584573 |archivedate=18 September 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and ex-Muslim, on '[[:wikt:murtad|murtad]] under Islamic Sharia'.]]
{{Main|Religion in Libya}}
Atheism is prohibited in [[Libya]] and can come with a death penalty, if one is charged as an atheist.<ref name="itcadel.gov.ly">{{cite web |url=http://itcadel.gov.ly/wp-content/uploads/pdfs2013/add04-2016.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2017-08-29 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829172621/http://itcadel.gov.ly/wp-content/uploads/pdfs2013/add04-2016.pdf |archivedate=29 August 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

In June 2013, Libya's General National Council assembly (GNC) voted to make Islamic Sharia law the basis for all legislation and for all state institutions, a decision having an impact in banking, criminal, and financial law.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-law-idUSBRE9B30M220131204 |title=Libyan assembly votes to follow Islamic law |accessdate=2016-11-23 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161128050741/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-libya-law-idUSBRE9B30M220131204 |archivedate=28 November 2016 |df=dmy-all |newspaper=Reuters |date=2013-12-04 }}</ref>
In February 2016, Libya's General National Council assembly (GNC) released adecree No.20 Changing on provisions of the Libyan Penal Code.<ref name="itcadel.gov.ly"/>

=== Malaysia ===
[[File:Datuk Seri Shahidan Kassim.jpg|thumb|Minister [[Shahidan Kassim]]: "The Federal Constitution does not recognise people without religion (...).<br />I suggest we hunt them down."<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thesundaily.my/news/2017/08/08/minister-urges-govt-hunt-down-atheist-group |title=Minister urges govt to hunt down atheist group |work=[[The Sun (Malaysia)]] |date=8 August 2017 |accessdate=10 December 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170817055846/http://www.thesundaily.my/news/2017/08/08/minister-urges-govt-hunt-down-atheist-group |archivedate=17 August 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>]]
{{Main|Freedom of religion in Malaysia|Human rights in Malaysia|Blasphemy law in Malaysia|Capital punishment in Malaysia}}
{{See also|Religion in Malaysia}}
[[Islam in Malaysia|Malaysia]] does not have a [[Law of Malaysia|national law]] that criminalizes apostasy and its Article 11 grants freedom of religion to its diverse population of different religions.<ref name=aamalaysia>Adil & Azam (2007), Law of apostasy and freedom of religion in Malaysia, Asian Journal of Comparative Law, 2(1) (May 2007); {{doi|10.2202/1932-0205.1060}}</ref> However, Malaysia's constitution grants its states (''Negeri'') the power to create and enforce laws relating to Islamic matters and Muslim community.<ref name=aamalaysia/> State laws in [[Kelantan]] and [[Terengganu]] make apostasy in Islam a crime punishable with death, while state laws of [[Perak]], [[Malacca]], [[Sabah]], and [[Pahang]] declare apostasy by Muslims as a crime punishable with jail terms. In these states, apostasy is defined as conversion from Islam to another faith, but converting to Islam is not a crime. The central government has not attempted to nullify these state laws, but stated that any death sentence for apostasy would require review by national courts.<ref name=malaysiaapo>[https://www.state.gov/documents/organization/222357.pdf Malaysia 2013 International Religious Freedom Report] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170504002350/https://www.state.gov/documents/organization/222357.pdf |date=4 May 2017 }} U.S. Department of State International Law Research (2014)</ref><ref>Kamali (1998), Punishment in Islamic law: A critique of the hudud bill of Kelantan Malaysia, Arab Law Quarterly, 13(3): 203–34</ref> Ex-Muslims can be fined, jailed or sent for [[counselling]].<ref name="Eleftheriou">{{Cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/malaysia-atheist-group-muslim-apostate-members-lapsed-faith-south-east-asia-a7881301.html |title=Malaysian atheist group under investigation over alleged Muslim apostate members |author=Loulla-Mae Eleftheriou-Smith |work=The Independent |date=8 August 2017 |accessdate=26 November 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171210073450/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/malaysia-atheist-group-muslim-apostate-members-lapsed-faith-south-east-asia-a7881301.html |archivedate=10 December 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

National laws of Malaysia require Muslim apostates who seek to convert from Islam to another religion to first obtain approval from a sharia court. The procedure demands that anyone born to a Muslim parent, or who previously converted to Islam, must declare himself apostate of Islam before a Sharia court if he or she wants to convert. The Sharia courts have the power to impose penalties such as jail, caning and enforced "rehabilitation" on apostates – which is the typical practice. In the states of Perak, Malacca, Sabah, and Pahang, apostates of Islam face jail term; in Pahang, caning; others, confinement with rehabilitation process.<ref name=malaysiaapo/>

The state laws of Malaysia allow apostates of other religion to become Muslim without any equivalent review or process. The state laws of [[Perak]], [[Kedah]], [[Negeri Sembilan]], [[Sarawak]], and [[Malacca]] allow one parent to convert children to Islam even if the other parent does not consent to his or her child's conversion to Islam.<ref name=malaysiaapo/>

In a highly public case, the Malaysian Federal Court did not allow [[Lina Joy]] to change her religion status in her I/C in a 2–1 decision.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}

In August 2017, a picture from a gathering of the [[Atheist Republic]] Consulate of [[Kuala Lumpur]] was posted on Atheist Republic's Facebook page. Deputy Minister of Islamic Affairs [[Asyraf Wajdi Dusuki]] ordered an inquiry into whether anyone in the picture had committed apostasy or had 'spread atheism' to any Muslims present, both of which are illegal in Malaysia.<ref name="Cleef">{{Cite news |url=https://www.trouw.nl/home/in-maleisie-geldt-gij-zult-geen-atheist-zijn-~ab9d88f0/ |title=In Maleisië geldt: gij zult geen atheïst zijn |author=Wouter van Cleef |work=[[Trouw]] |date=7 August 2017 |accessdate=18 September 2017 |language=nl |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170918110440/https://www.trouw.nl/home/in-maleisie-geldt-gij-zult-geen-atheist-zijn-~ab9d88f0/ |archivedate=18 September 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name="Eleftheriou"/> The next day, Minister in the Prime Minister's Department [[Shahidan Kassim]] stated atheists should be "hunted down", as there was no place for groups like this under the [[Constitution of Malaysia|Federal Constitution]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.themalaymailonline.com/malaysia/article/atheists-in-malaysia-should-be-hunted-down-minister-says#exc7KOAQFT4yGG8v.97 |title=Atheists in Malaysia should be hunted down, minister says |author=Kamles Kumar |work=[[Malay Mail]] |date=8 August 2017 |accessdate=27 November 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171210074632/http://www.themalaymailonline.com/malaysia/article/atheists-in-malaysia-should-be-hunted-down-minister-says#exc7KOAQFT4yGG8v.97 |archivedate=10 December 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name="Atkins">{{Cite episode |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p05b9q23 |title=What's it like being an atheist in Malaysia? |last=Atkins |first=Ros |series=[[BBC OS]] |format=radio |publisher=BBC World Service |date=9 August 2017 |accessdate=26 November 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813233816/http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p05b9q23 |archivedate=13 August 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Atheist Republic (AR) members present at the gathering reportedly received death threats on social media.<ref name="Cleef"/><ref name="Eleftheriou"/> Canada-based AR leader [[Armin Navabi]] asked: "How is this group harming anyone?", warning that such actions by the government damaged Malaysia's reputation as a "moderate" Muslim-majority (60%) country.<ref name="Cleef"/> The uploads sparked violent protests from some Malaysians calling Navabi an 'apostate' and threatening to [[beheading|behead]] him.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnnindonesia.com/internasional/20170808202316-106-233346/malaysia-buru-muslim-yang-datangi-perkumpulan-ateis/ |title=Malaysia Buru Muslim yang Datangi Perkumpulan Ateis |author=Lesthia Kertopati |work=CNN Indonesia |date=8 August 2017 |accessdate=27 November 2017 |language=id |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171205041601/https://www.cnnindonesia.com/internasional/20170808202316-106-233346/malaysia-buru-muslim-yang-datangi-perkumpulan-ateis/ |archivedate=5 December 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> A Kuala Lumpur AR Consulate admin told ''[[BBC OS]]'' that such meetings are just socialising events for 'people who are legally Muslim, and atheists, and people from other religions as well'.<ref name="Atkins"/> In November 2017, it was reported that Facebook had rejected a joint government and [[Malaysian Communications and Multimedia Commission]] demand to shut down Atheist Republic's page and similar atheist pages, because the pages did not violate any of the company's [[community standards]].<ref name="unconstitutional">{{Cite news |url=http://www.todayonline.com/world/atheism-unconstitutional |title=Atheism is unconstitutional, says Malaysian deputy minister |work=[[Today (Singapore newspaper)|Today Online]] |publisher=Mediacorp |date=23 November 2017 |accessdate=26 November 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201030715/http://www.todayonline.com/world/atheism-unconstitutional |archivedate=1 December 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

=== Maldives ===
[[File:Dr Zakir Naik.jpg|thumb|[[Zakir Naik]]: "If the person who becomes a non-Muslim propagates his faith and speaks against Islam [where] there is Islamic rule, then the person is to be put to death."<ref name="apostat3"/>]] 
{{Main|Irreligion in the Maldives}}
{{See also|Freedom of religion in the Maldives|Islam in the Maldives}}
The [[Constitution of the Maldives|Constitution]] of the [[Maldives]] designates [[Islam]] as the official [[state religion]], and the government and many citizens at all levels interpret this provision to impose a requirement that all citizens must be Muslims. The Constitution states the president must be a [[Sunni Islam|Sunni Muslim]]. There is no [[freedom of religion]] [[freedom of thought|or belief]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://freethoughtreport.com/countries/asia-southern-asia/maldives/ |title=Maldives |work=Freedom of Thought Report |publisher=[[International Humanist and Ethical Union]] |accessdate=12 November 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171112073946/http://freethoughtreport.com/countries/asia-southern-asia/maldives/ |archivedate=12 November 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> This situation leads to institutionally sanctioned religious oppression against non-Muslims and ex-Muslims who currently reside in the country.

On 27 April 2014, the Maldives ratified a new regulation that revived the [[death penalty]] (abolished in 1953, when the last execution took place) for a number of ''[[hudud]]'' offences, including apostasy for persons from the age of 7 and older. The new regulation was strongly criticised by the [[Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights]] and the [[European Union|EU]]'s [[High Representative of the Union for Foreign Affairs and Security Policy|High Representative]], pointing out that they violated the [[Convention on the Rights of the Child]] and the [[International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights]], which the Maldives have ratified, that ban the execution of anyone for offences committed before the age of 18.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/asia/2014/04/maldives-enacts-regulation-death-penalty-2014430214541593659.html |title=Maldives enacts regulation for death penalty |work=Al Jazeera English |date=1 May 2014 |accessdate=12 November 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171113003356/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/asia/2014/04/maldives-enacts-regulation-death-penalty-2014430214541593659.html |archivedate=13 November 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=47680#.WgeIfWjWyUl |title=Maldives should repeal new regulation providing for death penalty, says UN rights office |work=UN News Centre |publisher=United Nations |date=29 April 2014 |accessdate=12 November 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171112185642/http://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=47680#.WgeIfWjWyUl |archivedate=12 November 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

During a question-and-answer session at one of Indian Muslim orator [[Zakir Naik]]'s lectures 29 May 2010 on the [[Maldives]], 37-year-old Maldivian citizen Mohamed Nazim stated that he was struggling to believe in any religion, and did not consider himself to be a Muslim. He further asked what his verdict would be under Islam and in the Maldives.<ref name="apostat3">{{Cite news |url=https://minivannewsarchive.com/files/2010/05/Dr_Zakir_Naik_and_Nazim-1.pdf |title=Transcript of Dr Zakir Naik's response to Mohamed Nazim |work=[[Minivan Daily]] |date=28 May 2010 |accessdate=6 December 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171207020012/https://minivannewsarchive.com/files/2010/05/Dr_Zakir_Naik_and_Nazim-1.pdf |archivedate=7 December 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=apostat4>[http://www.haveeru.com.mv/english/details/30855 Maldivian renounces Islam, gets attacked by Zakir Naik audience] {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/60kifXA19?url=http://www.haveeru.com.mv/english/details/30855 |date=2011-08-07 }} Haveeru Daily (English Ed.) 2010-05-30</ref> Zakir responded that he considers the punishment for apostasy not necessarily to mean death, since [[Muhammed]] was reported in the Hadith scriptures to have shown [[clemency]] towards apostates on some occasions, but added that "If the person who becomes a non-Muslim propagates his faith and speaks against Islam [where] there is Islamic rule, then the person is to be put to death."<ref name="apostat3"/> Mohamed Nazim was subsequently reported to have been arrested and put in [[protective custody]] by the Maldivian Police. He later publicly reverted to Islam in custody after receiving two days of counseling by two Islamic scholars, but was held awaiting possible charges.<ref name=apostat5>[http://www.haveeru.com.mv/english/details/30892 What will happen to the Maldivian who renounced Islam?] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100830192009/http://www.haveeru.com.mv/english/details/30892 |date=30 August 2010 }} Haveeru Daily (English Ed.) 2010-05-31</ref><ref name=apostat6>[http://www.haveeru.com.mv/english/details/30901 Maldivian who renounced Islam reverts back] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101212011825/http://www.haveeru.com.mv/english/details/30901 |date=12 December 2010 }} Haveeru Daily (English Ed.) 2010-06-01</ref><ref name=apostat7>[http://minivannews.com/politics/islamic-foundation-calls-for-death-sentence-if-apostate-fails-to-repent-7606 Islamic Foundation calls for death sentence if apostate fails to repent] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100602084013/http://minivannews.com/politics/islamic-foundation-calls-for-death-sentence-if-apostate-fails-to-repent-7606 |date=2 June 2010 }} Minivan News 2010-05-30</ref>

On 14 July 2010, Maldivian news site ''Minivan News''<ref>{{cite web|url = http://minivannews.com/society/hanged-air-traffic-controller-sought-asylum-for-fear-of-religious-persecution-9381|title = Hanged air traffic controller sought asylum for fear of religious persecution|author = JJ Robinson|publisher = Minivan News|date = 14 July 2010|deadurl = yes|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100717005713/http://minivannews.com/society/hanged-air-traffic-controller-sought-asylum-for-fear-of-religious-persecution-9381|archivedate = 17 July 2010|df = dmy-all}}</ref> reported that 25-year-old air traffic controller Ismail Mohamed Didi had sent two e-mails, dated 25 June, to an international human rights organisation, declaring that he was an atheist ex-Muslim and that he desired help with his asylum application (directed to the United Kingdom). This came after he had "foolishly admitted my stance on religion" to his colleagues at work two years earlier, word of which had "spread like wildfire", and led to increased repression from colleagues, family, and even his closest friends shunning him, and anonymous death threats over the telephone. The same day that the report was posted, Didi was found hanged at his workplace in the aircraft control tower at [[Malé International Airport]] in an apparent suicide.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/mobile/world-south+asia-10644685 |title=Maldives atheist who felt persecuted 'hangs himself' |author=Charles Haviland |publisher=BBC News |date=15 July 2010 |accessdate=12 November 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171129041441/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/mobile/world-south+asia-10644685 |archivedate=29 November 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

=== Mauritania ===
{{Main|Freedom of religion in Mauritania|Human rights in Mauritania}}
{{See also|Religion in Mauritania}}
[[File:Mohamed Cheikh Ould Mkhaitir (cropped).png|thumb|Blogger [[Mohamed Cheikh Ould Mkhaitir|Ould Mkhaitir]], accused of apostasy, overturned his death sentence in 2017.]]

Article 306 of the criminal code of [[Mauritania]] declares apostasy in Islam as illegal and provides a death sentence for the crime of leaving Islam.<ref name=maurit>[https://www.loc.gov/law/help/apostasy/index.php#mauritania Mauritania - Laws Criminalizing Apostasy] {{webarchive|url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20171231144725/https://www.loc.gov/law/help/apostasy/index.php |date=31 December 2017 }} Library of Congress (May 2014)</ref> Its law provides a provision where the guilty is given the opportunity to repent and return to Islam within three days. Failure to do so leads to a death sentence, dissolution of family rights and property confiscation by the government. The Mauritanian law requires that an apostate who has repented should be placed in custody and jailed for a period for the crime.<ref name=maurit/> Article 306 reads:

<blockquote>All Muslims guilty of apostasy, either spoken or by overt action will be asked to repent during a period of three days. If he does not repent during this period, he is condemned to death as an apostate, and his belongings confiscated by the State Treasury.<ref name="Ibn Warraq">{{Cite web |url=http://www.newenglishreview.org/Ibn_Warraq/Apostasy,_Human_Rights,_Religion_and_Belief/ |title=Apostasy, Human Rights, Religion and Belief |author=Ibn Warraq |work=New English Review |date=January 2016 |accessdate=11 December 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171211165514/http://www.newenglishreview.org/Ibn_Warraq/Apostasy,_Human_Rights,_Religion_and_Belief/ |archivedate=11 December 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref></blockquote>

In 2014, Jemal Oumar, a Mauritanian journalist, was arrested for apostasy, after he posted a critique of Mohammad online.<ref>[http://allafrica.com/stories/201401120133.html Mauritanians Condemn Call to Kill Author] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140819195028/http://allafrica.com/stories/201401120133.html |date=19 August 2014 }} All Africa (10 January 2014)</ref> While local law enforcement agencies held him in prison for trial, local media announced offers by local Muslims of cash reward to anyone who would kill Jemal Oumar.<br />
In a separate case, [[Mohamed Cheikh Ould Mkhaitir|Mohamed Mkhaitir]], a Mauritanian engineer, was arrested with the accusation of apostasy and blasphemy in 2014 as well, for publishing an essay on the racist caste system in Mauritanian society with criticism of Islamic history and a claim that Mohammad discriminated in his treatment of people from different tribes and races.<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/6SEx7P7Pf?url=http://www.jadaliyya.com/pages/index/17914/religion-race-and-repression-in-mauritania_the-oul Religion, Race, and Repression in Mauritania: The Ould Mkhaitir Apostasy Affair] Jadaliyya, Mauritania (29 May 2014)</ref> Supported by pressure from human rights activists and international diplomats, Mkhaitir's case was reviewed several times, amid public civilian protests calling for him to be killed.<ref name="quash">{{Cite web |url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2017/11/07/mauritania-quash-blogger-mkhaitirs-death-sentence |title=Mauritania: Quash Blogger Mkhaitir's Death Sentence |publisher=Human Rights Watch |date=7 November 2017 |accessdate=11 November 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180320224424/https://www.hrw.org/news/2017/11/07/mauritania-quash-blogger-mkhaitirs-death-sentence |archivedate=20 March 2018 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> On 8 November 2017 the Court of Appeals decided to convert his death sentence into a two-year jail term, which he had already served, so he was expected to be released soon.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/live/world-africa-41926318 |title=Mauritanian blogger escapes death penalty |author=Natasha Booty & Dickens Olewe |work=BBC News |date=9 November 2017 |accessdate=11 November 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171111003539/http://www.bbc.com/news/live/world-africa-41926318 |archivedate=11 November 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> However, by May 2018 he still had not been released according to human rights groups.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://africatimes.com/2018/05/12/rights-groups-speak-out-on-mauritanian-blogger-blasphemy-law/ |title=Rights groups speak out on Mauritanian blogger, blasphemy law |work=Africa Times |date=12 May 2018 |accessdate=28 June 2018}}</ref>

=== Morocco ===
[[File:Imad Iddine Habib on Blasphemy and Apostasy in Morocco.webm|thumb|Imad Iddine Habib on blasphemy and apostasy in Morocco.]]
{{Main|Religion in Morocco#Freedom of religion|Irreligion in Morocco|Human rights in Morocco}}
The penal code of [[Morocco]] does not impose the death penalty for apostasy. However, Islam is the official state religion of Morocco under its constitution. Article 41 of the Moroccan constitution gives fatwa powers (habilitée, religious decree legislation) to the Supreme Council of Religious Scholars, which issued a religious decree, or ''[[fatwa]]'', in April 2013 that Moroccan Muslims who leave Islam must be sentenced to death.<ref name=morocco>[https://www.loc.gov/law/help/apostasy/index.php#morocco Morocco – Laws Criminalizing Apostasy] {{webarchive|url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20171231144725/https://www.loc.gov/law/help/apostasy/index.php |date=31 December 2017 }} Library of Congress (May 2014)</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://morocconewstribune.com/moroccos-high-council-of-ulemass-death-sentence-fatwa-on-apostates-sparks-controversy |title=Morocco's high council of Ulemas's death sentence fatwa on apostates sparks controversy | website=Morocco News Tribune |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130430050358/http://morocconewstribune.com/moroccos-high-council-of-ulemass-death-sentence-fatwa-on-apostates-sparks-controversy|archivedate=30 April 2013 |date=April 2013 |access-date=17 April 2015}}</ref>  However, Mahjoub El Hiba, a senior Moroccan government official, denied that the fatwa was in any way legally binding.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.middle-east-online.com/english/?id=58230 |title=Fatwa to kill apostates sparks fierce controversy in Morocco |date=18 April 2013 |website=Middle East online |access-date=7 April 2015 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150418050541/http://www.middle-east-online.com/english/?id=58230 |archivedate=18 April 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> This decree was retracted by the Moroccan High Religious Committee in February 2017 in a document titled "The Way of the Scholars."<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moroccoworldnews.com/2017/02/207505/moroccos-high-religious-committee-says-apostates-should-not-be-killed/|title=Morocco's High Religious Committee Says Apostates Should Not Be Killed|date=2017-02-06|website=Morocco World News|access-date=2017-08-30|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170830235538/https://www.moroccoworldnews.com/2017/02/207505/moroccos-high-religious-committee-says-apostates-should-not-be-killed/|archivedate=30 August 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It instead states that apostasy is a political stance rather than a religious issue, equatable to 'high treason'.

When he was 14, Imad Iddine Habib came out as an atheist to his family, who expelled him. Habib stayed with friends, got a degree in Islamic studies and founded the Council of Ex-Muslims of Morocco in 2013. Secret services started investigating him after a public speech criticising Islam, and Habib fled to England, after which he was sentenced to seven years in prison in absentia.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/apr/10/losing-my-religion-life-after-extreme-belief-faith |title=Losing my religion: life after extreme belief |author=Shahesta Shaitly |work=The Guardian |date=10 April 2016 |accessdate=14 September 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170914034311/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/apr/10/losing-my-religion-life-after-extreme-belief-faith |archivedate=14 September 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

=== Netherlands ===
{{See also|Religion in the Netherlands}}
In the [[Netherlands]], a country in Western Europe, [[Islam in the Netherlands|Muslims made up]] about 4.9% of the total population as of 2015; the rest of its inhabitants were either non-religious (50.1%), Christian (39.2%) or adherents of various other religions (5.7%).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cbs.nl/nl-nl/nieuws/2016/51/helft-nederlanders-is-kerkelijk-of-religieus |title=Helft Nederlanders is kerkelijk of religieus |publisher=[[Statistics Netherlands]] |date=22 December 2016 |accessdate=9 December 2017 |language=nl |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171017201934/https://www.cbs.nl/nl-nl/nieuws/2016/51/helft-nederlanders-is-kerkelijk-of-religieus |archivedate=17 October 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Although the freedom of expression, thought and religion is guaranteed by law in the Netherlands, there is doubt concerning the reality of this individual freedom within the small orthodox Christian minorities and within Muslim communities. The social and cultural pressure for those raised in a conservative religious family not to change or 'lose' religion can be high. This lack of 'horizontal' freedom (the freedom in relation to family, friends and neighborhood) remains a concern. Ex-Muslims often keep their views hidden from family, friends and the wider community.<ref name="FOTR17nl">{{Cite web |url=http://freethoughtreport.com/countries/europe-western-europe/netherlands/ |title=Netherlands |work=Freedom of Thought Report 2017 |publisher=International Humanist and Ethical Union |date=4 December 2017 |accessdate=9 December 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171210071828/http://freethoughtreport.com/countries/europe-western-europe/netherlands/ |archivedate=10 December 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

[[File:2Doc- Onder Ongelovigen (Trailer).webm|thumb|''[[Among Nonbelievers]]'', a 2015 Dutch–English film about ex-Muslims.]]
[[Ayaan Hirsi Ali]] deconverted from Islam after seeing the [[September 11 attacks]] being justified by [[Al Qaeda]]'s leader [[Osama bin Laden]] with verses from the Quran that she verified personally, and subsequently reading [[Herman Philipse]]'s ''[[Atheïstisch manifest]]'' ("Atheist Manifesto"). She soon became a prominent critic of Islam amidst an increasing number of death threats from Islamists and thus a need for security.<ref name=h071222>{{cite web |url=http://thehumanist.com/magazine/january-february-2008/features/absolute-infidel-the-evolution-of-ayaan-hirsi-ali |work=The Humanist |date=22 December 2007 |accessdate=9 December 2017 |author=David Schaefer |author2=Michelle Koth |title=Absolute Infidel: The Evolution of Ayaan Hirsi Ali |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180117002916/https://thehumanist.com/magazine/january-february-2008/features/absolute-infidel-the-evolution-of-ayaan-hirsi-ali |archivedate=17 January 2018 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> She was [[Dutch general election, 2003|elected to Parliament in 2003]] for the [[People's Party for Freedom and Democracy|VVD]], and co-producing [[Theo van Gogh (film director)|Theo van Gogh]]'s short film ''[[Submission (2004 film)|Submission]]'' (broadcast on 29 August 2004), which criticised the treatment of [[women and Islam|women in Islamic society]].<ref name="Parool">{{cite web |url=https://www.parool.nl/amsterdam/dit-schreef-het-parool-na-de-moord-op-theo-van-gogh~a4528656/ |title=Dit schreef Het Parool na de moord op Theo van Gogh |work=Het Parool |date=2 November 2017 |accessdate=10 December 2017 |language=nl |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171210123542/https://www.parool.nl/amsterdam/dit-schreef-het-parool-na-de-moord-op-theo-van-gogh~a4528656/ |archivedate=10 December 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> This led to even more death threats, and [[Assassination of Theo van Gogh|Van Gogh was assassinated]] on 2 November 2004 by jihadist terrorist [[Hofstad Network]] leader [[Mohammed Bouyeri]].<ref name="Parool"/> He threatened Hirsi Ali and other nonbelievers by writing that her "apostasy had turned her away from the truth", "only death can separate truth from lies", and that she would "certainly perish".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.trouw.nl/home/onderkrant-open-brief-aan-hirsi-ali~a948a9c7/ |title=Onderkrant {{!}} Open brief aan Hirsi Ali |work=Trouw |date=5 November 2004 |accessdate=9 December 2017 |language=nl |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171210071850/https://www.trouw.nl/home/onderkrant-open-brief-aan-hirsi-ali~a948a9c7/ |archivedate=10 December 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Gone into hiding and heavily protected, she received a string of international awards, including one of [[Time 100|''Time''{{'}}s 100 most influential people of the world]], for her efforts at highlighting Islam's violation of human rights, especially women's rights, before moving to the United States in 2006 following a [[Second Balkenende cabinet#2006 cabinet crisis|Dutch political crisis over her citizenship]].<ref name=h071222/>

[[Ehsan Jami]], co-founder of the [[Central Committee for Ex-Muslims]] in the Netherlands in 2007, has received several death threats, and due to the amount of threats its members received, the Committee was dismantled in 2008.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.nu.nl/algemeen/1528962/ehsan-jami-heft-comite-ex-moslims-op-video.html |title=Ehsan Jami heft comité ex-moslims op (video) |work=Nu.nl |date=16 April 2008 |accessdate=9 December 2017 |language=nl |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171019020043/https://www.nu.nl/algemeen/1528962/ehsan-jami-heft-comite-ex-moslims-op-video.html |archivedate=19 October 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> To fill this lacuna, the [[Humanistisch Verbond|Dutch Humanist Association]] (HV) launched the Platform of New Freethinkers in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://nieuwevrijdenkers.nl/ |title=Platform Nieuwe Vrijdenkers |publisher=Humanistisch Verbond |accessdate=11 December 2017 |language=nl |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924155910/http://nieuwevrijdenkers.nl/ |archivedate=24 September 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> There is a Dutch-speaking group for Muslim apostates born and/or raised in the Netherlands, and an English-speaking one for ex-Muslims who recently arrived in the Netherlands as refugees. The latter fled their country because they were discriminated against or confronted with threats, violence or persecution because of their humanist or atheist life-stance.<ref name="FOTR17nl"/> The HV and [[Humanistische Omroep]] cooperated under the direction of Dorothée Forma to produce two documentaries on both groups: ''[[Among Nonbelievers]]'' (2015) and ''[[Non-believers: Freethinkers on the Run]]'' (2016).<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nrc.nl/nieuws/2016/12/12/documentaire-ongelovig-vrijdenkers-op-de-vlucht-npo-2-2255-2350u-5767639-a1536303 |title=Ongelovig: vrijdenkers op de vlucht NPO 2, 22.55-23.50u. |work=NRC Handelsblad |date=12 December 2016 |accessdate=30 September 2017}}</ref>

=== Nigeria ===
[[File:Use of Sharia in Nigeria.svg|thumb|Status of sharia in Nigerian states (in 2013):<ref name="Ostien575">{{cite web|title="13. Sharia and national law in Nigeria", in: ''Sharia Incorporated: A Comparative Overview of the Legal Systems of Twelve Muslim Countries in Past and Present'' |url=http://www.lup.nl/do.php?a=process_visitor_download&editorial_id=1562 |author1=Philip Ostien  |author2=Albert Dekker  |lastauthoramp=yes |publisher=Leiden University Press |pages=575 (25) |year=2008 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141020031048/http://www.lup.nl/do.php?a=process_visitor_download&editorial_id=1562 |archivedate=20 October 2014 }}</ref><br/>
{{legend|#706EA4|Sharia applies in full, including criminal law}}
{{legend|#F6DD4F|Sharia applies only in personal status issues}}
{{legend|#179C86|No sharia}}]]
{{See also|Religion in Nigeria|Islamic extremism in Northern Nigeria|Religious violence in Nigeria|Blasphemy law in Nigeria|Human rights in Nigeria}}
In [[Nigeria]], there is no federal law that explicitly makes apostasy a crime. The [[Constitution of Nigeria|Federal Constitution]] protects freedom of religion and allows religious conversion. Section 10 of the constitution states, 'The Government of the Federation of a State shall not adopt any religion as State Religion.'.<ref name="FOTR17ng">{{Cite web |url=http://freethoughtreport.com/countries/africa-western-africa/nigeria/ |title=Nigeria |work=Freedom of Thought Report 2017 |publisher=International Humanist and Ethical Union |date=4 December 2017 |accessdate=11 December 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171212084353/http://freethoughtreport.com/countries/africa-western-africa/nigeria/ |archivedate=12 December 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

However, 12 Muslim-majority states in northern Nigeria have laws invoking Sharia, which have been used to persecute Muslim apostates, particularly Muslims who have converted to Christianity.<ref>Ikenga Oraebunam (2012), ''Islamic Law, Religious Freedom and Human Rights in Nigeria'', African Journal of Law and Criminology, Volume 2 Number 1, pp. 1–25</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.refworld.org/docid/50068bbf2.html |title=Nigeria: Recent reports regarding the treatment of persons who convert from Islam to Christianity. Recent reports on Sharia law in relation to religious conversion, Ireland: Refugee Documentation Centre, 26 June 2012, Q15539|website=www.refworld.org|accessdate=11 December 2017}}</ref> Although the states of Nigeria have a degree of autonomy to adopt their own laws, the first paragraph of the Federal Constitution stipulates that any law inconsistent with the provisions of the constitution shall be void.<ref name="Harnisch106">{{Cite book |last=Harnischfeger |first=Johannes |date=2008 |title=Democratization and Islamic Law: The Sharia Conflict in Nigeria |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ftfXThvfQHkC&pg=106 |location=Frankfurt am Main |publisher=Campus Verlag |page=106 |isbn=978-3593382562 |accessdate=11 December 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180320224424/https://books.google.com/books?id=ftfXThvfQHkC&pg=106 |archivedate=20 March 2018 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The Sharia penal code does contradict the Constitution, yet the federal government has not made a move to restore this breach of the constitutional order, letting the northern Muslim-dominated states have their way and not protecting the constitutional rights of citizens violated by Sharia.<ref name="Harnisch106"/>

Governor [[Ahmad Sani Yerima]] of [[Zamfara State]], the first Nigerian Muslim-majority state to introduce Sharia in 2000, stated that because capital punishment for apostasy was unconstitutional, citizens themselves should do the killing, effectively undermining the [[rule of law]]:<ref name="Harnisch106"/>

<blockquote>If you change your religion from Islam, the penalty is death. We know it. And we didn't put it in our penal code because it is against the constitutional provision. It is the law of Allah, which now is a culture for the entire society. So if a Muslim changes his faith or religion, it is the duty of the society or family to administer that part of the justice to him.<ref name="Harnisch106"/></blockquote>

Sani further added that whoever opposed 'the divine rules and regulations (...) is not a Muslim',<ref name="Harnisch106"/> confirmed by Secretary-General of the Nigerian Supreme Council for Islamic Affairs [[Lateef Adegbite]], who was quoted as saying:

<blockquote>Once you reject sharia, you reject Islam. So, any Muslim that protests the application of sharia is virtually declaring himself non-Muslim.<ref name="Harnisch106"/></blockquote>

In December 2005, Nigerian pastor Zacheous Habu Bu Ngwenche was attacked for allegedly hiding a convert.<ref name=marshall20080410/>

=== Oman ===
{{Main|Freedom of religion in Oman|Human rights in Oman}}
{{See also|Religion in Oman}}
[[Oman]] does not have an apostasy law. However, under Law 32 of 1997 on Personal Status for Muslims, an apostate's marriage is considered annulled and inheritance rights denied when the individual commits apostasy.<ref name=omanapo>[https://www.loc.gov/law/help/apostasy/index.php#oman Oman –  Laws Criminalizing Apostasy] {{webarchive|url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20171231144725/https://www.loc.gov/law/help/apostasy/index.php |date=31 December 2017 }} Library of Congress (May 2014)</ref> The Basic Law of Oman, since its enactment in 1995, declares Oman to be an Islamic state and Sharia as the final word and source of all legislation. Omani jurists state that this deference to Sharia, and alternatively the blasphemy law under Article 209 of Omani law, allows the state to pursue death penalty against Muslim apostates, if it wants to.<ref name=omanapo/><ref>A Saeed, Muslim debates on human rights and freedom of religion, in Human Rights in Asia, Editors: Thomas W.D. Davis and Brian Galligan, {{ISBN|978-1848446809}}, p. 34</ref>

=== Palestine ===
[[File:Waleed Al-Husseini interview.webm|thumb|[[Maryam Namazie]] interviews Palestinian ex-Muslim [[Waleed Al-Husseini]] (2016).]]
{{Main|Freedom of religion in the State of Palestine}}
The [[State of Palestine]] does not have a constitution; however, the Basic Law provides for religious freedom. The Basic Law was approved in 2002 by the Palestinian Legislative Council (PLC) and signed by then-President [[Yasir Arafat]]. The Basic Law states that Islam is the official religion, but also calls for respect and sanctity for other "heavenly" religions (such as Judaism and Christianity) and that the principles of Shari'a (Islamic law) shall be the main source of legislation.<ref name="FOTRPalestine">{{Cite web |url=http://freethoughtreport.com/countries/asia-western-asia/palestine/ |title=Palestine |work=Freedom of Thought Report |publisher=[[International Humanist and Ethical Union]] |date=2016 |accessdate=14 September 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170914043027/http://freethoughtreport.com/countries/asia-western-asia/palestine/ |archivedate=14 September 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

The Palestinian Authority (PA) requires Palestinians to declare their religious affiliation on identification papers. Either Islamic or Christian ecclesiastical courts handle legal matters relating to personal status. Inheritance, marriage, and divorce are handled by such courts, which exist for Muslim and Christians.<ref name="FOTRPalestine"/>

Citizens living in the West Bank found to be guilty of 'defaming religion' under the old Jordanian law, run the risk of years of imprisonment, up to for life. This happened to 26-year-old blogger [[Waleed Al-Husseini]] in October 2010, who was arrested and charged with defaming religion after openly declaring himself an atheist and criticising religion online.<ref name="FOTRPalestine"/> He was detained for ten months. After being released, he eventually fled to France, as the PA continued to harass him, and citizens called for him to be lynched.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dw.de/when-muslims-renounce-their-faith/a-17574172 |title=When Muslims renounce their faith |author=Naomi Conrad |newspaper=Deutsche Welle |date=17 April 2014 |accessdate=14 September 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150530001937/http://www.dw.de/when-muslims-renounce-their-faith/a-17574172 |archivedate=30 May 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He later found out he was sentenced to seven-and-a-half years in prison in absentia.

=== Pakistan ===
{{Main|Freedom of religion in Pakistan|Human rights in Pakistan|Blasphemy law in Pakistan|Capital punishment in Pakistan}}
{{See also|Islamization of Pakistan|Religion in Pakistan}}
[[File:Islam's Non-Believers Panel Discussion.webm|thumb|Ex-Muslim [[Fauzia Ilyas]], co-founder of Atheist and Agnostic Alliance Pakistan, tells her story (15:53–19:02).]]

As of 2014, there is no law that criminalizes apostasy in Pakistan.<ref name=Goitom>Goitom, Hannibal. "Laws Criminalizing Apostasy in Selected Jurisdictions," ''[[Law Library of Congress]]'', May 2014.</ref> A bill was proposed in 2007 to criminalize apostasy, but it failed to pass. 
It has been noted that, in theory, the principle of "[[Non liquet|a lacuna]]" could apply where a gap in statute law could be filled with Islamic law. However, as of 2014, there were no known cases of anyone being prosecuted for apostasy in Pakistan.<ref name=Goitom/> Apostates can be prosecuted under Pakistan's blasphemy law, if they desecrate the Quran or make derogatory remarks against the Islamic [[Prophet Muhammad]].<ref name=pakistan>[https://www.loc.gov/law/help/apostasy/index.php#pakistan Pakistan - Laws Criminalizing Apostasy] {{webarchive|url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20171231144725/https://www.loc.gov/law/help/apostasy/index.php |date=31 December 2017 }} Library of Congress (May 2014)</ref> Further, Pakistan has blasphemy law that carries death penalty, but the law does not define blasphemy. Under Article 295-C of its penal code, any Pakistani Muslim who feels his or her religious feelings have been hurt, directly or indirectly, for any reason or any action of another Pakistani citizen can accuse blasphemy and open a criminal case against anyone.<ref>[http://in.reuters.com/article/2014/05/20/pakistan-blasphemy-tv-stations-idINKBN0E00Y420140520 Ballooning Pakistan blasphemy charges engulf television stations] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140903103632/http://in.reuters.com/article/2014/05/20/pakistan-blasphemy-tv-stations-idINKBN0E00Y420140520 |date=3 September 2014 }} Reuters (20 May 2014)</ref> Inheritance and property rights for apostates was prohibited by Pakistan in 1963.<ref name=dforte2>Forte, D. F. (1994), Apostasy and Blasphemy in Pakistan, Conn. Journal of Int'l Law, Vol. 10, pp. 27–41</ref>

In 1991, Tahir Iqbal, whose had converted to Christianity from Islam, was arrested on charges of desecrating a copy of the Qur'an and making statements against Muhammad. While awaiting trial, he was denied bail on the presumption by a Sessions Court and the appeals Division of the [[Lahore High Court]] that conversion from Islam was a "cognizable offense". However, it has been noted by multiple sources that there conversion from Islam is not an offense under Pakistani law.<ref name=Goitom/><ref name=tahiriqbal>[https://www.webcitation.org/6SF5LW6yd?url=http://www.hrw.org/reports/1993/pakistan/ Persecuted Minorities and Writers in Pakistan] Human Rights Watch, Vol 5, No. 13 (19 September 1993)</ref><ref>[http://www.pakistanchristianpost.com/viewarticles.php?editorialid=254 Apostasy from Islam in Pakistan] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140903121320/http://www.pakistanchristianpost.com/viewarticles.php?editorialid=254 |date=3 September 2014 }} Stephen Gill (2009)</ref> In 1992, a local imam asked Iqbal to be sentenced to death for converting to Christianity. The Pakistani judge hearing the case rejected the idea, saying that Iqbal could only be sentenced if it could be proven he had committed blasphemy.<ref name=tahiriqbal/>

In 2016, Pakistan's Sindh province passed legislation to protect religious freedom by banning forced conversions of people, Sindh has a large Hindu minority compared to other Pakistani provinces.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://tribune.com.pk/story/1243091/sindh-assembly-passes-bill-forced-religious-conversions/ |title= Sindh Assembly passes bill against forced religious conversions |work= The Express Tribune |date= 24 November 2016 |deadurl= no |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20161124160445/http://tribune.com.pk/story/1243091/sindh-assembly-passes-bill-forced-religious-conversions/ |archivedate= 24 November 2016 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>

=== Qatar ===
{{Main|Freedom of religion in Qatar|Human rights in Qatar|Blasphemy law#Qatar}}
{{See also|Religion in Qatar}}
Apostasy in Islam is a crime in [[Qatar]].<ref name=pew2012laws/> Its Law 11 of 2004 specific traditional Sharia prosecution and punishment for apostasy, considering it a hudud crime punishable by death penalty.<ref name=locqatar>[https://www.loc.gov/law/help/apostasy/index.php#qatar Qatar – Laws Criminalizing Apostasy] {{webarchive|url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20171231144725/https://www.loc.gov/law/help/apostasy/index.php |date=31 December 2017 }} Library of Congress (May 2014)</ref>

Proselytizing of Muslims to convert to another religion is also a crime in Qatar under Article 257 of its law,<ref name=locqatar/> punishable with prison term. According to its law passed in 2004, if proselytizing is done in Qatar, for any religion other than Islam, the sentence is imprisonment of up to five years. Anyone who travels to and enters Qatar with written or recorded materials or items that support or promote conversion of Muslims to apostasy are to be imprisoned for up two years.<ref>[http://eclj.org/pdf/070911_eclj_aclj_report.pdf International Legal Protection of the Right to Choose One’s Religion and Change One’s Religious Affiliation] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304043653/http://eclj.org/pdf/070911_eclj_aclj_report.pdf |date=4 March 2016 }} European Center for Law and Justice (2007)</ref>

Casual discussion or "sharing one's faith" with any Muslim resident in Qatar has been deemed a violation of Qatari law, leading to deportation or prison time.<ref>[https://travel.state.gov/content/passports/english/country/qatar.html Qatar – Country Report] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905114705/http://travel.state.gov/content/passports/english/country/qatar.html |date=5 September 2015 }} U.S. State Department (2013)</ref> There is no law against proselytizing non-Muslims to join Islam.

=== Saudi Arabia ===
[[File:Rescuing Ex-Muslims – Leaving Islam.png|thumb|The 2016 [[Vice News]] film ''Rescuing Ex-Muslims: Leaving Islam'' documents the case of Saudi ex-Muslim Rana Ahmad fleeing to Germany.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.faz.net/aktuell/politik/saudi-arabien-flucht-vor-der-religion-14286388.html?printPagedArticle=true#pageIndex_0 |title=Flucht vor der Religion |author=Charlotte Sophie Meyn |work=Frankfurter Allgemeiner Zeitung |date=16 June 2016 |accessdate=13 September 2017 |language=de |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170830002934/http://www.faz.net/aktuell/politik/saudi-arabien-flucht-vor-der-religion-14286388.html?printPagedArticle=true#pageIndex_0 |archivedate=30 August 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>]]
{{Main|Freedom of religion in Saudi Arabia|Human rights in Saudi Arabia|Blasphemy law in Saudi Arabia|Capital punishment in Saudi Arabia}}
{{See also|Wahhabism|Committee for the Promotion of Virtue and the Prevention of Vice (Saudi Arabia)|Religion in Saudi Arabia}}
[[Saudi Arabia]] has no penal code, and defaults its [[Legal system of Saudi Arabia|law entirely to Sharia]] and its implementation to religious courts. The case law in Saudi Arabia, and consensus of its jurists is that Islamic law imposes the death penalty on apostates.<ref>[https://www.loc.gov/law/help/apostasy/index.php#saudiarabia Saudi Arabia - Laws Criminalizing Apostasy] {{webarchive|url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20171231144725/https://www.loc.gov/law/help/apostasy/index.php |date=31 December 2017 }} Library of Congress (May 2014)</ref>

Apostasy law is actively enforced in Saudi Arabia.  For example, Saudi authorities charged [[Hamza Kashgari]], a Saudi writer, in 2012 with apostasy based on comments he made on Twitter. He fled to Malaysia, where he was arrested and then extradited on request by Saudi Arabia to face charges.<ref>[https://www.hrw.org/news/2012/02/13/saudi-arabia-writer-faces-apostasy-trial Saudi Arabia: Writer Faces Apostasy Trial] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131016090120/http://www.hrw.org/news/2012/02/13/saudi-arabia-writer-faces-apostasy-trial |date=16 October 2013 }}, Human Rights Watch (13 Feb. 2012)</ref> Kashgari repented, upon which the courts ordered that he be placed in protective custody. Similarly, two Saudi Sunni Muslim citizens were arrested and charged with apostasy for adopting the [[Persecution of Ahmadis|Ahmadiyya]] sect of Islam.<ref>U.S. Department of State, Bureau of Democracy, Human Rights and Labor, [https://www.state.gov/documents/organization/208622.pdf International Religious Freedom Report for 2012: Saudi Arabia] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170504021258/https://www.state.gov/documents/organization/208622.pdf |date=4 May 2017 }} (20 May 2013)</ref> As of May 2014, the two accused of apostasy had served two years in prison awaiting trial.<ref>[http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Middle-East/2014/May-15/256556-hrw-urges-saudi-to-free-two-ahmadis-held-for-apostasy.ashx#axzz3BwArkFYL HAW urges Saudi to free two Ahmadis held for apostasy] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151124162753/http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Middle-East/2014/May-15/256556-hrw-urges-saudi-to-free-two-ahmadis-held-for-apostasy.ashx |date=24 November 2015 }}, The Daily Star, Lebanon News (15 May 2014)</ref>

In 2015, a man in Saudi Arabia was sentenced to death for apostasy.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/saudiarabia/11431509/Saudi-Arabia-court-gives-death-penalty-to-man-who-renounced-his-Muslim-faith.html | title=Saudi Arabia court gives death penalty to man who renounced his Muslim faith| date=2015-02-24| last1=Spencer| first1=Richard}}</ref>

In 2012, the US Department of State alleged that Saudi Arabia's school textbooks included chapters which justified the social exclusion and killing of apostates.<ref>U.S. Department of State, Bureau of Democracy, Human Rights and Labor, [https://www.state.gov/documents/organization/208622.pdf International Religious Freedom Report for 2012: Saudi Arabia] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170504021258/https://www.state.gov/documents/organization/208622.pdf |date=4 May 2017 }} (20 May 2013), pp. 1–2</ref>

=== Somalia ===
[[File:Amal Farah Secular Conference 2015.webm|thumb|Ex-Muslim Amal Farah on Somali attitudes to apostasy.]]
{{Main|Human rights in Somalia|Capital punishment in Somalia}}
{{See also|Religion in Somalia}}
Apostasy is a crime in [[Somalia]].<ref name=pew2012laws>[http://www.pewforum.org/2012/11/21/laws-penalizing-blasphemy-apostasy-and-defamation-of-religion-are-widespread/ Laws Penalizing Blasphemy, Apostasy and Defamation of Religion are Widespread] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131011231914/http://www.pewforum.org/2012/11/21/laws-penalizing-blasphemy-apostasy-and-defamation-of-religion-are-widespread/ |date=11 October 2013 }} Pew Research, Washington DC (21 November 2012)</ref> Articles 3(1) and 4(1) of Somalia's constitution declare that religious law of Sharia is the nation's highest law. The prescribed punishment for apostasy is the death penalty.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=An-Na'im |first1=Abdullahi A. |title=Religious Minorities under Islamic Law and the Limits of Cultural Relativism |journal=Human Rights Quarterly |date=1987 |volume=9 |issue=1 |pages=1–18 |doi=10.2307/761944 |jstor=761944}}</ref><ref>[http://unpos.unmissions.org/LinkClick.aspx?fileticket=RkJTOSpoMME= CONSTITUTION] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402122013/http://unpos.unmissions.org/LinkClick.aspx?fileticket=RkJTOSpoMME%3D |date=2 April 2015 }} Federal Republic of Somalia, United Nations (2012)</ref>

There have been numerous reports of executions of people for apostasy, particularly Muslims who have converted to [[Christianity in Somalia|Christianity]]. However, the reported executions have been by extra-state Islamist groups and local mobs, rather than after the accused has been tried under a Somali court of law.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/7833621.stm Somali executed for 'apostasy'] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090117083418/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/7833621.stm |date=17 January 2009 }} BBC News, 16 January 2009</ref><ref>[http://www.assistnews.net/Stories/2010/s10070036.htm Somali Islamists Execute Christian Convert] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029133449/http://www.assistnews.net/Stories/2010/s10070036.htm |date=29 October 2013 }} Jeremy Reynalds, ANS (7 July 2010)</ref>

=== Sudan ===
[[File:Nahla Mahmoud interviewed by Maryam Namazie.webm|thumb|Sudanese human rights activist [[Nahla Mahmoud]] and [[Maryam Namazie]] discuss ex-Muslims in Sudan.]]
{{Main|Freedom of religion in Sudan|Human rights in Sudan|Blasphemy law in Sudan|Capital punishment in Sudan}}
{{See also|Islamization of Sudan|Religion in Sudan}}
Article 126.2 of the Penal Code of [[Sudan]] (1991) reads,
<blockquote>Whoever is guilty of apostasy is invited to repent over a period to be determined by the tribunal. If he persists in his apostasy and was not recently converted to Islam, he will be put to death.<ref name="Ibn Warraq"/></blockquote>

Some notable cases of apostasy in Sudan include: [[Mahmoud Mohammed Taha]], a Sudanese religious thinker, leader, and trained engineer, who was executed for "sedition and apostasy" in 1985 at the age of 76 by the regime of [[Gaafar Nimeiry]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20061003184013/http://www.iheu.org/node/1307 Apostacy – International Humanist and Ethical Union]</ref><ref name=packer>[http://www.newyorker.com/archive/2006/09/11/060911fa_fact1 The Moderate Martyr] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407015421/http://www.newyorker.com/archive/2006/09/11/060911fa_fact1 |date=7 April 2014 }}: A radically peaceful vision of Islam| by George Packer| 11 September 2006</ref>  [[Meriam Ibrahim]], a 27-year-old Christian Sudanese woman was sentenced to death for apostasy in May 2014, but allowed to leave the country in July after an international outcry.<ref name=tran>{{cite news|last1=Tran|first1=Mark|title=Sudanese woman spared death sentence for apostasy arrives in Italy|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/24/sudanese-woman-meriam-ibrahim-spared-death-sentence-apostasy-italy|accessdate=30 July 2014|publisher=The Guardian|date=24 July 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140801094956/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/24/sudanese-woman-meriam-ibrahim-spared-death-sentence-apostasy-italy|archivedate=1 August 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

Sudanese ex-Muslim and human rights activist [[Nahla Mahmoud]] has estimated that during the years 2010, 2011 and 2012, there have been between 120 and 170 Sudanese citizens who have been convicted for apostasy, most of whom repented to avoid a death sentence.<ref name="Garçon">{{Cite news |url=http://www.slateafrique.com/103275/religions-afrique-tuera-dieu |title=L'Afrique tuera-t-elle Dieu? |author=Lou Garçon |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate Afrique]] |date=27 October 2016 |accessdate=17 April 2018 |language=fr}}</ref>

=== Tunisia ===
Following the 2010–11 [[Tunisian Revolution]], a Constituent Assembly worked for 2.5 years to written a new Constitution, approved in January 2014, contained a provision in Article 6 granting freedom of conscience.<ref name="Ghribi">{{Cite news |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2014/01/09/the-problem-with-tunisias-new-constitution/ |title=The Problem with Tunisia's New Constitution |author=Asma Ghribi |work=[[Foreign Policy]] |date=9 January 2014 |accessdate=6 October 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171006111946/http://foreignpolicy.com/2014/01/09/the-problem-with-tunisias-new-constitution/ |archivedate=6 October 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/law/help/apostasy/#tunisia|title=Laws Criminalizing Apostasy|publisher=Library of Congress|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160217025829/http://www.loc.gov/law/help/apostasy/#tunisia|archivedate=17 February 2016|df=dmy-all|date=June 2014}}</ref> It also stipulates that '[a]ccusations of apostasy and incitement to violence are prohibited'.<ref name="Ghribi"/> With it, Tunisia became the first Arab-majority country to protect its citizens from prosecution for renouncing Islam.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://en.qantara.de/content/interview-with-rachid-ghannouchi-if-you-sow-dictatorship-you-harvest-terrorism |title="If you sow dictatorship, you harvest terrorism" |author=Daniel Bax and Tsafrir Cohen |work=Qantara.de |date=31 December 2014 |accessdate=6 October 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171006062825/https://en.qantara.de/content/interview-with-rachid-ghannouchi-if-you-sow-dictatorship-you-harvest-terrorism |archivedate=6 October 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Critics have pointed out alleged flaws of this formulation, namely that it violates the freedom of expression.<ref name="Ghribi"/>

The highest profile cases of apostasy in Tunisia were of the two atheist ex-Muslims [[Trial of Ghazi Beji and Jabeur Mejri|Ghazi Beji and Jabeur Mejri]], sentenced to 7.5 years in prison on 28 March 2012. They were prosecuted for expressing their views on Islam, the Quran and Muhammad on Facebook, blogs and in online books, which allegedly 'violated public order and morality'. Mejri wrote a treatise in English on Muhammad's supposedly violent and sexually immoral behaviour.<ref name="Mulder">{{Cite news |url=https://www.trouw.nl/home/je-leven-niet-zeker-zonder-geloof~a93a1cd6/ |title=Je leven niet zeker zonder geloof |author=Eildert Mulder |work=Trouw |date=20 April 2012 |accessdate=11 November 2017 |language=nl |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171019020419/https://www.trouw.nl/home/je-leven-niet-zeker-zonder-geloof~a93a1cd6/ |archivedate=19 October 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> When Mejri was arrested by police, he [[forced confession|confessed under torture]]<ref name="lExpress">{{Cite news |url=http://www.lexpress.fr/actualite/jabeur-mejri-en-tunisie-les-affames-se-mangent-entre-eux_1498886.html |title=Jabeur Mejri: "En Tunisie, les affamés se mangent entre eux" |author=Karim Ben Said |work=[[L'Express]] |date=11 March 2014 |accessdate=7 October 2017 |language=fr |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171007070226/http://www.lexpress.fr/actualite/jabeur-mejri-en-tunisie-les-affames-se-mangent-entre-eux_1498886.html |archivedate=7 October 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name="Mulder"/> that his friend Beji had also authored an antireligious book, ''The Illusion of Islam'', in Arabic. Upon learning he, too, was sought by the police, Beji fled the country and reached [[Greece]];<ref name="Mulder"/> he obtained political asylum in France on 12 June 2013.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.france24.com/fr/20130613-tunisie-ghazi-beji-caricature-prophete-mahomet-blaspheme-asile-politique-france |title=Condamné pour blasphème en Tunisie, Ghazi Beji obtient l'asile politique en France |author=Assiya Hamza |work=France 24 |date=14 June 2013 |accessdate=6 October 2017 |language=fr |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171007021545/http://www.france24.com/fr/20130613-tunisie-ghazi-beji-caricature-prophete-mahomet-blaspheme-asile-politique-france |archivedate=7 October 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Mejri was pardoned by president [[Moncef Marzouki]] and left prison on 4 March 2014<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.rfi.fr/afrique/20140305-caricatures-mahomet-le-tunisien-jabeur-mejri-est-sorti-prison |title=Caricatures de Mahomet: le Tunisien Jabeur Mejri est sorti de prison |work=[[Radio France Internationale]] |date=5 March 2014 |accessdate=6 October 2017 |language=fr |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171007021144/http://www.rfi.fr/afrique/20140305-caricatures-mahomet-le-tunisien-jabeur-mejri-est-sorti-prison |archivedate=7 October 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> after several human rights groups campaigned for his release under the slogan "Free Jabeur".<ref name="lExpress"/><ref name="HuffPost Maghreb"/> When Mejri wanted to accept [[Sweden]]'s invitation to move there, he was again imprisoned for several months, however, after being accused of embezzling money from his former job by his ex-colleagues<ref name="HuffPost Maghreb">{{Cite news |url=http://www.huffpostmaghreb.com/2014/10/15/jabeur-mejri_n_5988354.html |title=Tunisie: Grâcié par la présidence, Jabeur Mejri a été libéré |work=HuffPost Maghreb |date=15 October 2014 |accessdate=7 October 2017 |language=fr |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171007120115/http://www.huffpostmaghreb.com/2014/10/15/jabeur-mejri_n_5988354.html |archivedate=7 October 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> (who started bullying him as soon as they found out he was an atheist),<ref name="lExpress"/><ref name="Mulder"/> a rumour spread by his former friend Beji<ref name="lExpress"/> (who felt betrayed by Mejri because he had outed him as an atheist).<ref name="Mulder"/>

=== Turkey ===
{{See also|Freedom of religion in Turkey}}
Although there is no punishment for apostasy from Islam in Turkey, there are several formal and informal mechanisms in place that make it hard for citizens not to be Muslim. Non-Muslims, especially non-religious people, are discriminated against in a variety of ways. Article 216 of the penal code outlaws insulting religious belief, a de facto blasphemy law obstructing citizens from expressing irreligious views, or views critical of religions. A well-known example is that of pianist [[Fazıl Say]] in 2012, who was charged with insulting religion for publicly declaring his atheism. Irreligious Turks are also often discriminated against in the workplace, because people are assumed to be Muslim by birth, and terms such as 'atheist' or 'nonbeliever' are frequently used insults in the public sphere.<ref name="FOTR17tr">{{Cite web |url=http://freethoughtreport.com/countries/asia-western-asia/turkey/ |title=Turkey |work=Freedom of Thought Report 2017 |publisher=International Humanist and Ethical Union |date=4 December 2017 |accessdate=19 April 2018}}</ref>

In 2014, the Turkish atheist association [[Ateizm Derneği]] was founded for nonreligious citizens, many of whom have left Islam. The association won the [[International League of non-religious and atheists]]'s Sapio Award 2017 for being the first officially recognised organisation in the Middle East defending the rights of atheists.<ref name="Wakonigg">{{Cite news |url=https://hpd.de/artikel/es-sollte-keinen-mut-erfordern-muessen-atheist-sein-14538 |title="Es sollte keinen Mut erfordern müssen, Atheist zu sein" |author=Daniela Wakonigg |work=Diesseits |publisher=Humanistischer Pressedienst |date=17 June 2017 |accessdate=19 April 2018 |language=de}}</ref>

An early April 2018 report of the Turkish Ministry of Education, titled "The Youth is Sliding to Deism", observed that an increasing number of pupils in [[İmam Hatip school]]s was abandoning Islam in favour of [[deism]]. The report's publication generated large-scale controversy amongst conservative Muslim groups in Turkish society. Progressive Islamic theologian Mustafa Ozturk noted the deist trend a year earlier, arguing that the "very archaic, dogmatic notion of religion" held by the majority of those claiming to represent Islam was causing "the new generations [to get] indifferent, even distant, to the Islamic worldview." Despite lacking reliable statistical data, numerous anecdotes appear to point in this direction. Although some commentators claim the secularisation is merely a result of Western influence or even a "conspiracy", most commentators, even some pro-government ones, have come to conclude that "the real reason for the loss of faith in Islam is not the West but Turkey itself: It is a reaction to all the corruption, arrogance, narrow-mindedness, bigotry, cruelty and crudeness displayed in the name of Islam." Especially when the [[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|AKP]] Islamists are in power to enforce Islam upon society, this is making citizens turn their back on it.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2018/04/turkey-why-so-many-turks-are-losing-faith-in-islam.html |title=Why so many Turks are losing faith in Islam |author=[[Mustafa Akyol]] |work=[[Al-Monitor]] |date=16 April 2018 |accessdate=19 April 2018}}</ref>

=== United Arab Emirates ===
{{Main|Freedom of religion in the United Arab Emirates|Human rights in United Arab Emirates|Blasphemy law in the United Arab Emirates|Capital punishment in the United Arab Emirates}}
{{See also|Religion in the United Arab Emirates}}
Apostasy is a crime in the [[United Arab Emirates]].<ref name=uae>[https://www.loc.gov/law/help/apostasy/index.php#uae UAE –  Laws Criminalizing Apostasy] {{webarchive|url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20171231144725/https://www.loc.gov/law/help/apostasy/index.php |date=31 December 2017 }} Library of Congress (May 2014)</ref> In 1978, UAE began the process of Islamising the nation's law, after its council of ministers voted to appoint a High Committee to identify all its laws that conflicted with Sharia. Among the many changes that followed, UAE incorporated [[hudud]] crimes of Sharia into its Penal Code - apostasy being one of them.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Al-Muhairi |first1=Butti Sultan Butti Ali |title=The Islamisation of Laws in the UAE: The Case of the Penal Code |journal=Arab Law Quarterly |date=1996 |volume=11 |issue=4 |pages=350–371 |doi=10.2307/3381546 |jstor=3381546}}</ref> Article 1 and Article 66 of UAE's Penal Code requires hudud crimes to be punished with the death penalty.<ref>[https://archive.is/20070626035050/http://www.gcc-legal.org/MojPortalPublic/DisplayLegislations.aspx?country=2&LawTreeSectionID=3947 Articles of Law 3 of 1987], al Jarida al Rasmiyya, vol. 182, 8 December 1987</ref><ref>Al-Muhairi (1997), Conclusion to the Series of Articles on the UAE Penal Law. Arab Law Quarterly, Vol. 12, No. 4</ref>

UAE law considers it a crime and imposes penalties for using the Internet to preach against Islam or to proselytize Muslims inside the international borders of the nation. Its laws and officials do not recognize conversion from Islam to another religion. In contrast, conversion from another religion to Islam is recognized, and the government publishes through mass media an annual list of foreign residents who have converted to Islam.<ref>[https://www.state.gov/documents/organization/208628.pdf United Arab Emirates 2012 International Religious Freedom Report] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170504022854/https://www.state.gov/documents/organization/208628.pdf |date=4 May 2017 }} U.S. Department of State (2013)</ref>

=== United Kingdom ===
{{Main|Freedom of religion in the United Kingdom|Human rights in United Kingdom|Blasphemy law in the United Kingdom|Capital punishment in United Kingdom}}
{{See also|Islamization of Europe|Religion in United Kingdom}}
[[File:ExMuslimBecause video.webm|thumb|[[Council of Ex-Muslims of Britain|CEMB]]'s #ExMuslimBecause campaign, late 2015.]]

The [[Council of Ex-Muslims of Britain]] (CEMB) is the British branch of the [[Central Council of Ex-Muslims]], who represent former [[Muslim]]s who fear for their lives because they have renounced Islam. It was launched in [[Westminster]] on 22 June 2007. The Council protests against Islamic states that still punish Muslim apostates with death under the Sharia law. The Council is led by [[Maryam Namazie]], who was awarded ''[[Secularist of the Year]]'' in 2005 and has faced death threats.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2007/06/21/wrushdie221.xml|title=New group for those who renounce Islam|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=18 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080210015649/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=%2Fnews%2F2007%2F06%2F21%2Fwrushdie221.xml|archive-date=10 February 2008|dead-url=yes|publisher=The Daily Telegraph|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The [[British Humanist Association]] and [[National Secular Society]] sponsored the launch of the organisation and have supported its activities since.<ref>Maryam Namazie: [http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/WO0706/S00319.htm Launch of the Council of ex-Muslims of Britain] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170102115142/http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/WO0706/S00319.htm |date=2 January 2017 }}, ''[[Scoop (news website)|Scoop]]'', 19 June 2007</ref> A July 2007 poll by the [[Policy Exchange]] think-tank revealed that 31% of British Muslims believed that leaving the Muslim religion should be punishable by death.<ref>{{cite web
 |year        = 2007
 |url         = http://www.policyexchange.org.uk/images/publications/living%20apart%20together%20-%20jan%2007.pdf
 |title       = Living Apart Together
 |work        = Policy Exchange
 |publisher   = Policy Exchange
 |accessdate  = 2013-07-03
 |deadurl     = yes
 |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20131102045124/http://www.policyexchange.org.uk/images/publications/living%20apart%20together%20-%20jan%2007.pdf
 |archivedate = 2 November 2013
 |df          = dmy-all
}}</ref>

CEMB assists about 350 apostates a year, the majority of whom have faced death threats from Islamists or family members.<ref name=theguardian_17May2015>{{Cite news|last1=Anthony|first1=Andrew|title=Losing their religion: the hidden crisis of faith among Britain's young Muslims|url=https://www.theguardian.com/global/2015/may/17/losing-their-religion-british-ex-muslims-non-believers-hidden-crisis-faith|newspaper=The Guardian|date=17 May 2015|accessdate=17 September 2017|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912074528/https://www.theguardian.com/global/2015/may/17/losing-their-religion-british-ex-muslims-non-believers-hidden-crisis-faith|archivedate=12 September 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The number of ex-Muslims is unknown due to a lack of sociological studies on the issues and the reluctance of ex-Muslims to discuss their status openly.<ref name=theguardian_17May2015/> Writing for ''[[The Observer]]'' Andrew Anthony argued that ex-Muslims had failed to gain support from other progressive groups, due to caution about being labelled by other progressive movements as [[Islamophobic]] or [[racist]].<ref name=theguardian_17May2015/>

In November 2015, the CEMB launched the social media campaign #ExMuslimBecause, encouraging ex-Muslims to [[coming out|come out]] as apostates, and explain why they left Islam. Within two weeks, the hashtag had been used over a 100,000 times. Proponents argued that it should be possible to freely question and criticise Islam, opponents claimed the campaign was amongst other things 'hateful', and said the extremist excrescences of Islam were unfairly equated with the religion as a whole.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-34975848 |title=Ex-Muslims give reasons they left the faith, using a hashtag |author1=Anne-Marie Tomchak |author2=Greg Brosnan |lastauthoramp=yes |work=[[BBC News]] |date=1 December 2015 |accessdate=21 December 2015 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151224022338/http://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-34975848 |archivedate=24 December 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

Besides the CEMB, a new initiative for ex-Muslims, [[Faith to Faithless]], was launched by Imtiaz Shams and [[Aliyah Saleem]] in early 2015.<ref name=theguardian_17May2015/><ref name="wrn2017">{{cite web|last1=Meyer|first1=Elisa|title=How one woman left Islam to campaign for atheism|url=http://www.worldreligionnews.com/religion-news/one-woman-left-islam-campaign-atheism|website=World Religion News|accessdate=17 September 2017|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170917123346/http://www.worldreligionnews.com/religion-news/one-woman-left-islam-campaign-atheism|archivedate=17 September 2017|df=dmy-all|date=2016-11-26}}</ref>

=== United States ===
{{See also|Freedom of religion in the United States|Irreligion in the United States}}
[[File:Sarah Haider introduces Ex-Muslims of North America.webm|thumb|[[Sarah Haider]] introduces [[Ex-Muslims of North America]].]]
According to [[Pew Research Center]] estimate in 2016, there were about 3.3 million [[Islam in the United States|Muslims living in the United States]], comprising about 1% of the total [[United States|U.S.]] population.<ref name="Pew U.S. Muslims">{{cite web|url=http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2016/01/06/a-new-estimate-of-the-u-s-muslim-population/|title=A new estimate of the U.S. Muslim population|date=6 January 2016|work=Pew Research Center|accessdate=17 December 2016}}</ref> A 2015 survey by the Pew Research Center found that 23% of Americans who were raised as Muslims no longer identify with Islam.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.pewforum.org/2015/05/12/chapter-2-religious-switching-and-intermarriage/#retention-of-childhood-members-hindus-muslims-and-jews-most-successful-at-retaining-adherents |title=Retention of Childhood Members: Hindus, Muslims and Jews Most Successful at Retaining Adherents |website= |publisher=Pew Research Center |date=12 May 2015 |accessdate=21 March 2018}}</ref><ref name="EconomistMarch18"/> However, many of them are not open about their deconversion, in fear of endangering their relationships with their relatives and friends.<ref name="EconomistMarch18">{{Cite news |url=https://www.economist.com/news/united-states/21738904-yet-even-land-free-apostasy-isnt-easy-number-ex-muslims-america |title=The number of ex-Muslims in America is rising |author= |work=The Economist |date=15 March 2018 |accessdate=21 March 2018}}</ref>

David B. Barrett, co-author of the ''[[World Christian Encyclopedia]]'', estimated around 2000 that in the United States annually 50,000 Christians converted to Islam while 20,000 Muslims adopted Christianity.<ref name="WashTimes">{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2002/oct/13/20021013-092358-6523r/ |title=Daring leaps of faith |author=[[Julia Duin]] |work=The Washington Times |date=13 October 2002 |accessdate=21 March 2018}}</ref> A 2002 article in ''[[The Washington Times]]'' by [[Julia Duin]] described the precarious situation of U.S. Muslim converts to Christianity: "Some have simply been shunned by their families. Others have been kidnapped by family members and friends, and put on a plane back home. All are reluctant to ask for protection from U.S. law enforcement, especially those converts with Arabic surnames who are leery of getting their names on a U.S. police report. However, there are no known instances of converts from Islam to Christianity who have been killed in the United States for their decision to leave their faith."<ref name="WashTimes"/> [[Ibn Warraq]], author of ''[[Why I Am Not a Muslim]]'' (1995) and ''[[Leaving Islam: Apostates Speak Out]]'' (2003), stressed the importance of this fact as a reason for 'not exaggerating' the fate of former Muslims in America, noting however: "They are threatened. They are attacked physically. I cite [in ''Leaving Islam''] instances of young students who have converted and who were attacked but were rescued just in time."<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.c-span.org/video/?155377-1/leaving-islam-apostates-speak-out&start=1201 |title=Leaving Islam: Apostates Speak Out, Jun 24 2003 |author=[[Ibn Warraq]] |work=[[C-SPAN]] |date=24 June 2003 |accessdate=21 March 2018}}</ref>{{rp|at=19:36}}

Well-known organisations who support ex-Muslims in the United States include [[Ex-Muslims of North America]] (EXMNA, co-founded by [[Muhammad Syed]], [[Sarah Haider]] and others), [[Former Muslims United]] and [[Muslimish]].

=== Yemen ===
{{Main|Freedom of religion in Yemen|Human rights in Yemen|Blasphemy law in Yemen|Capital punishment in Yemen}}
{{See also|Religion in Yemen}}
Apostasy is a crime in [[Yemen]]. Articles 12 and 259 of the Yemen Penal Code address apostasy, the former requires Sharia sentence be used for apostasy and the latter specifies death penalty for apostates of Islam.<ref>[https://www.loc.gov/law/help/apostasy/index.php#yemen Yemen – Laws Criminalizing Apostasy] {{webarchive|url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20171231144725/https://www.loc.gov/law/help/apostasy/index.php |date=31 December 2017 }} Library of Congress (May 2014)</ref> Yemeni law waives the punishment to an apostate if he or she recants, repents and returns to Islam while denouncing his or her new faith.

In 2012, Yemeni citizen Ali Qasim Al-Saeedi was arrested and charged with apostasy by Yemeni law enforcement agency after he posted his personal views questioning the teachings of Islam, on a Yemeni blogging site and his Facebook page.<ref>[http://www.rnw.nl/english/article/repent-or-die-yemen "Repent or die" in Yemen] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140903105340/http://www.rnw.nl/english/article/repent-or-die-yemen |date=3 September 2014 }} Radio Netherlands Worldwide (21 December 2012)</ref>

=== Other countries ===
{{Main|Freedom of religion by country}}
Apostasy is also a crime in smaller Muslim-majority countries such as [[Maldives]] and [[Comoros]].<ref name=pew2012laws/> In January 2006, in Turkey, Kamil Kiroglu was beaten unconscious and threatened with death if he refused to reject his Christian religion and return to Islam.<ref name=marshall20080410/>

==Universal Declaration of Human Rights==
{{Main|Human rights in Muslim-majority countries|Cairo Declaration on Human Rights in Islam}}
Laws prohibiting [[religious conversion]] run contrary<ref>Nisrine Abiad (2008), Sharia, Muslim States and International Human Rights Treaty Obligations, British Institute of International Comparative Law, {{ISBN|978-1905221417}}, pp. 25–31</ref> to Article 18 of the United Nations' [[Universal Declaration of Human Rights]], which states the following:

<blockquote>Everyone has the right to freedom of thought, conscience and religion; this right includes freedom to change his religion or belief, and freedom, either alone or in community with others and in public or private, to manifest his religion or belief in teaching, practice, worship and observance.<ref name="Un.org">{{cite web |url=https://www.un.org/en/documents/udhr/index.shtml#a18 |title=The Universal Declaration of Human Rights |publisher=Un.org |date= |accessdate=2013-11-29 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131128084554/http://www.un.org/en/documents/udhr/index.shtml#a18 |archivedate=28 November 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref></blockquote>

Afghanistan, Egypt, Iran, Iraq, Pakistan and Syria voted in favor of the Declaration.<ref name="Un.org"/> The governments of other Muslim-majority countries have responded by criticizing the Declaration as an attempt by the non-Muslim world to impose their values on Muslims, with a presumption of cultural superiority,<ref>{{cite book | last=Monteiro | first=A | title=Ethics of human rights | publisher=Springer | year=2014 | isbn=978-3-319-03566-6 | pages=414–16}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Said |first1=Abdul Aziz |title=Precept and Practice of Human Rights in Islam |journal=Universal Human Rights |date=1979 |volume=1 |issue=1 |pages=63–79 |doi=10.2307/761831 |jstor=761831}}</ref> and by issuing the [[Cairo Declaration on Human Rights in Islam]]—a joint declaration of the member states of the [[Organisation of the Islamic Conference]] made in 1990 in [[Cairo]], Egypt.<ref name = Brems>{{cite book | last = Brems | first = E | isbn = 978-90-411-1618-5 | title = Human rights: universality and diversity: Volume 66 of International studies in human rights | publisher = Martinus Nijhoff Publishers | year = 2001 | pages = 241–42, 259, 260–63 | chapter = Islamic Declarations of Human Rights }}</ref><ref name="Cismas p254"/> The Cairo Declaration differs from the Universal Declaration in affirming [[Sharia]] as the sole source of rights, and in limits of equality and behavior <ref>David Boersema, Philosophy of Human Rights: Theory and Practice, Westview Press, {{ISBN|978-0813344928}}</ref>{{Page needed|date=August 2010}}<ref>Denny F. M. (2005), Muslim ethical trajectories in the contemporary period, in The Blackwell companion to religious ethics (Editor: William Schweiker), {{ISBN|978-1405177580}}, Chapter 28, pp. 268–69, 272–77</ref><ref>Monshipouri (1998), Muslim World Half a Century after the Universal Declaration of Human Rights: Progress and Obstacles, The Netherlands Quarterly Hum. Rts., 16(3), pp. 289–90, 287–314</ref> in [[Islam and other religions|religion]],  [[Women in Islam|gender]], [[LGBT in Islam|sexuality]], etc.<ref name="Cismas p254">{{cite book | last=Cismas | first=Ioana | title=Religious actors and international law | publisher=Oxford University Press | location=Oxford, United Kingdom | year=2014 | isbn=978-0-19-871282-4 | pages=254, 258}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last=Cotran | first=Eugene | title=Yearbook of Islamic and Middle Eastern law, Volume 10 | publisher=Brill Academic Publishers | location=Boston | year=2006 | isbn=978-90-04-14444-6 | page=17}}</ref>
Islamic scholars such as Muhammad Rashid Rida in Tafsir al-Minar, argue that the "freedom to apostatize", is different from freedom of religion on the grounds that apostasy from Islam infringes on the freedom of others and the respect due the religion of Islamic states.<ref name=jstor-1570336/>

