{{Infobox mass murderer | name = Jožef Meneder | image = | image_size = | caption = | birth_name = | occupation = Soldier | birth_date = 1974 | birth_place = [[Subotica]], [[SFR Yugoslavia]] | death_date = {{BirthDeathAge| |1974| | |1993|6|3}} | death_place = [[Vranje]], [[FR Yugoslavia]] | cause = suicide | nationality = [[FR Yugoslavia]] | date = June 3, 1993 | time = | targets = soldiers | locations = [[Vranje]], [[FR Yugoslavia]] | fatalities = 8 (including the perpetrator) | injuries = 4 | weapons = automatic rifle, axe | motive = }}
'''Jožef Meneder''' ({{lang-sr-cyr|Јожеф Менедер}}, {{lang-hu|Meneder József}}; 1974 – 3 June 1993) was [[Serbia]]n-[[FR Yugoslavia]]n [[mass murderer]] of [[Hungarians in Serbia|Hungarian]] origin.<ref name="Minorities">{{cite web | url=http://www2.scc.rutgers.edu/serbiandigest/91/t91-3.htm | title=Minorities in the Army - The Hungarian Syndrome | publisher=[[Vreme]] |first1=Mirko|last1=Mlakar |first2=Filip|last2=Svarm |date=21 June 1993 | accessdate=2 June 2016}}</ref> On 3 June 1993, while serving as a private in the [[Serbia and Montenegro Military Forces|Army of FR Yugoslavia]] in the city of [[Vranje]], Meneder opened fire with an [[automatic rifle]], killing seven and wounding four fellow soldiers, before taking his own life.<ref name="Tribune">{{cite web | url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/doc/283602473.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jun%2004,%201993&author=Chicago%20Tribune%20wires.&pub=Chicago%20Tribune%20(pre-1997%20Fulltext)&edition=&startpage=&desc=Rampaging%20Yugoslav%20soldier%20guns%20down%208,%20kills%20himself | title=Rampaging Yugoslav soldier guns down 8, kills himself | publisher=Chicago Tribune | date=4 June 1993 | accessdate=2 June 2016}}</ref>
Meneder was kept in confinement of the military barracks of the South Morava brigade because of a barracks brawl. On 3 June 1993, just after the midnight, he managed to escape the cell, attacking the guard with an ax. He took an [[automatic rifle]] from the injured guard and opened a fire on the group of sleeping soldiers. He killed six men on the spot (one [[staff sergeant]] and five privates). One more later died as a result of their wounds. After that, he committed suicide.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.apnewsarchive.com/1993/Eight-Soldiers-Die-in-Barracks-Shooting-With-PM-Yugoslavia-Bjt/id-126f48851b99cafda460e626cda0ceee | title=EIGHT SOLDIERS DIE IN BARRACKS SHOOTING WITH PM-YUGOSLAVIA, BJT | publisher=The Associated Press | date=3 June 1993 | accessdate=2 June 2016}}</ref> The [[military police]] investigation found on his left arm a [[tattoo]] with a date "3 June 1993" and [[Satanism|Satanic]] [[symbol]]s in his home. It was discovered that he was a member of a Satanist [[Cult|religious cult]] called ''Loša vera'' (Serbian for "Bad religion").<ref name="Glas">{{cite web | url=http://arhiva.glas-javnosti.rs/arhiva/2003/10/11/srpski/F03101001.shtml | title=Nasilje kao deo obreda | publisher=[[Glas javnosti]] | date=11 October 2003 | accessdate=2 June 2016 | author=Luković, Zoran D. |trans-title=Violence as a ritual}}</ref>
