{{Format references|date=August 2013}} {{Infobox royalty | name = Marcus Ulpius Traianus (the Elder) | image = Bust of Marcus Ulpius Traianus the Elder at the National Museum of Serbia.jpg | caption = Bust of Marcus Ulpius Traianus at the [[National Museum of Serbia]], [[Belgrade]] | spouse = [[Marcia (mother of Trajan)|Marcia]] | issue = [[Trajan]] and [[Ulpia Marciana]] | father = Unknown | mother= Unknown | birth_date = c. 29 AD | birth_place = [[Italica]] | death_date = before 98 AD (aged 69) | death_place = Unknown }}
[[File:Trajan Divi Nerva.jpg|thumb|right|Roman aureus struck under Trajan, c. 115 AD. The reverse commemorates both Trajan's natural father, Marcus Ulpius Traianus (right), and his adoptive father, the Deified Nerva (left).]]
'''Marcus Ulpius Traianus Maior''' (c. 29 AD &ndash; before 98 AD; ''[[Latin]]'': ''Maior'', "the elder") was a [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] senator who lived in the 1st century. He was father to the Roman Emperor [[Trajan]].
==Family== Traianus belonged to the ''[[Ulpia (gens)|gens Ulpia]]'', originating from the [[Umbria]]n City of [[Tuder]], and was born and raised in the city of [[Italica]] (modern [[Santiponce]], near [[Seville]], [[Spain]]) in the Roman Province of [[Hispania Baetica]].<ref name=stro40>{{cite book|last1=Strobel|first1=Karl|title=Kaiser Traian|date=2010|publisher=Friedrich Pustet|location=Regensburg|isbn=9783791721729|page=40|language=German}}</ref> The Ulpii lived there from 206 BC, when the town was founded by [[Scipio Africanus|Publius Cornelius Scipio]], resettling wounded and invalid veterans of the wars against Carthage.<ref name=stro40/> The Ulpii, like the [[Aelia (gens)|Aelii]] and the Traii belonged to the leading [[Hispania|Hispano-Roman]] families of the city.<ref name=stro40/> From the latter family came a branch of the ancestors of Traianus, which intermarried with the Ulpii, originating the ''[[cognomen]]'' Traianus.<ref name=stro40/> Since the father of Traianus joined the ranks of the [[Patrician (ancient Rome)|Patricians]] in Rome, it is very likely that his grandfather had already belonged to the Roman Senate.<ref name=stro40/> His mother's origin is unknown. His sister [[Ulpia (grandmother of Hadrian)|Ulpia]] would be the mother of praetor [[Publius Aelius Hadrianus Afer]] (father of the [[Roman Emperor|Emperor]] [[Hadrian]]). Traianus married a Roman noblewoman called [[Marcia (mother of Trajan)|Marcia]].<ref name=stro41/> She was the elder sister of [[Marcia Furnilla]], the second wife of future Emperor [[Titus]], and consequently was in a position to help the career of her husband.<ref name=stro41>{{cite book|last1=Strobel|first1=Karl|title=Kaiser Traian|date=2010|publisher=Friedrich Pustet|location=Regensburg|isbn=9783791721729|page=41|language=German}}</ref> They had two children, a daughter called [[Ulpia Marciana]] and a son, the future Roman Emperor [[Trajan]].<ref name=stro41/> He was the maternal grandfather to [[Salonina Matidia]]; a maternal uncle to praetor [[Publius Aelius Hadrianus Afer]] and a paternal great-uncle to [[Hadrian]].
==Career== Traianus was possibly a senator by the reign of [[Claudius]].<ref name=stro41/> Before 67 AD, Traianus might have commanded a legion under the Roman General [[Gnaeus Domitius Corbulo]]. Under [[Vespasian]] (who was the Roman Governor of [[Judea]]), Traianus commanded the ''[[Legio X Fretensis|Legio X ''Fretensis'']]'' during the [[First Jewish–Roman War]] between 67-68 AD. During this time he came into favour with the future emperor.
As a result of his military successes, Vespasian awarded Traianus the [[Roman governor|governor]]ship of an unknown Roman [[Roman province|province]] and a [[Roman consul|suffect consulship]]. Paul Gallivan dated M. Ulpius Traianus the Elder to 70 based on his arrangement of the fragments of tablet E of the ''[[Fasti Ostienses]]'';<ref>Gallivan, [https://www.jstor.org/stable/638472 "The Fasti for A. D. 70-96"], ''[[Classical Quarterly]]'', 31 (1981), p. 187</ref> however, subsequent recovery of fragments allowed Ladislav Vidman to date Ulpius Traianus' tenure to September–October 72.<ref>Ladislaus Vidman, ed., ''Fasti Ostienses'', Second edition (Prague: Academia, 1982), pp. 73-75</ref> He was appointed governor of Cappadocia-Galatia (70/71 AD). He then served as governor of [[Syria (Roman province)|Syria]] in 73/74 AD, followed by a term as proconsul of [[Roman Asia]] in 79/80 AD. At an unspecified time he served as Governor of [[Hispania Baetica]].<ref>Werner Eck, "Jahres- und Provinzialfasten der senatorischen Statthalter von 69/70 bis 138/139", ''Chiron'', '''12''' (1982), pp. 281-362</ref> During his time in Syria, Traianus prevented a [[Parthia]]n invasion.
==Legacy== Traianus lived out his final years in honor and distinction. Indirect evidence suggests that he may have died before his son became emperor in 98 AD.<ref>Bennett (1997), p. 20</ref> Around 100 AD his son Trajan founded a colony in [[North Africa]]. This colony became a town and was called ''Colonia Marciana Ulpia Traiana Thamugadi'' (modern [[Timgad]], [[Algeria]]). His son named this town in honour of him, his late wife and his daughter. The colony’s name is also a tribute to his sister and his paternal ancestors. In 113 AD, Traianus was deified by his son, and his [[Aulic titulature|titulature]] reads ''divus Traianus pater''.
